text: Omodysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia, which is characterized by severe limb shortening and facial dysmorphism.

Ohdo syndrome is a type of syndrome that is characterized by blepharophimosis, ptosis, dental hypoplasia, hearing impairment, and intellectual disability. This syndrome includes at least the symptom of ptosis. Additionally, Ohdo syndrome has an exact synonym, Ohdo blepharophimosis syndrome.

Blepharophimosis intellectual disability syndrome SBBYS type, also known exactly as Ohdo syndrome, SBBYS Variant and Say-Barber-Biesecker-Young-Simpson syndrome, and relatedly referred to as SBBYSS, is a specific form of Ohdo syndrome. It falls under the category of conditions that at the very least present with symptoms like ptosis. This syndrome is defined by its characteristic features, which include blepharophimosis, ptosis, and intellectual disability.
Oculodentodigital dysplasia is a type of syndrome characterized by craniofacial, neurologic, limb, and ocular abnormalities. It is also exactly known as ODD syndrome.

X-linked chondrodysplasia punctata 1 is a type of chondrodysplasia punctata, which is a form of X-linked recessive disease. This condition is characterized by specific features including maxillary hypoplasia, stippled chondrodystrophy, a flat nasal tip, and short columella. Its material basis is rooted in both X-linked recessive inheritance and a deficiency of arylsulfatase E. Additionally, it is associated with vitamin K-related teratogenicity. X-linked chondrodysplasia punctata 1 is also known by its exact synonym, chondrodystrophia calcificans congenita.

Autosomal dominant chondrodysplasia punctata is a specific type of disease that falls under the broader categories of autosomal dominant diseases, chondrodysplasia punctata, and conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a chondrodysplasia punctata characterized by abnormal facies and stippling of the limbs, which is associated with vitamin K-related teratogenicity and has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Cold induced sweating syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by profuse sweating induced by cold ambient temperatures. Cold induced sweating syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms, Crisponi syndrome and Sohar-Crisponi syndrome.

Complement component 2 deficiency is a type of complement deficiency that is defined as a complement deficiency characterized by recurrent bacterial infections. It has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the C2 gene.

Congenital secretory chloride diarrhea 1 is characterized as a type of secretory diarrhea, autosomal recessive disease, physical disorder, and a condition with at least a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is associated with symptoms like diarrhea and has its disease basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The condition is defined by a secretory diarrhea that arises from a mutation in the SLC26A3 gene. Additionally, congenital secretory chloride diarrhea 1 is also known by exact synonyms including congenital chloride diarrhea Finnish type, congenital chloride diarrhoea Finnish type, congenital chloridorrhea, and congenital secretory chloride diarrhoea 1.
Complement component 4a deficiency is a type of complement deficiency characterized by recurrent bacterial infections, which are caused by C4A deficiency.
Complement component 4b deficiency is a type of complement deficiency, which is defined as a complement deficiency characterized by recurrent bacterial infections due to C4B deficiency.
Complement component 6 deficiency is a type of complement deficiency that is characterized by recurrent bacterial infections. It has a material basis in mutations in the C6 gene.
Complement component 7 deficiency is a type of complement deficiency, characterized by recurrent bacterial infections and has a material basis in mutation in the C7 gene.

Type I complement component 8 deficiency is a type of complement deficiency characterized by a deficiency of the alpha subunit of complement protein 8. This condition leads to an increased susceptibility to recurrent bacterial infections, especially to Neisseria meningitidis. It has a material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the C8A gene, which produces the alpha subunit of complement component 8 crucial in forming membrane attack complexes.

Type II complement component 8 deficiency is a type of complement deficiency that is defined by a deficiency of the beta subunit of complement protein 8. This condition leads to an increased susceptibility to recurrent bacterial infections, particularly to Neisseria meningitidis. The deficiency has a material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the C8B gene, which is responsible for producing the beta subunit of complement component 8, crucial for forming membrane attack complexes.
Complement component 9 deficiency is a type of complement deficiency, which is characterized by recurrent bacterial infections and has its material basis in a mutation in the C9 gene.
Dyschromatosis universalis hereditaria is a type of pigmentation disease, which is characterized by reticulate hyper- and hypo-pigmented macules in a generalized distribution.

Megalocornea is a type of corneal disease and an X-linked recessive disease, which specifically has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a bilaterally enlarged corneal diameter without an increase in intraocular pressure, a condition that is caused by a mutation in the CHRDL1 gene. Moreover, megalocornea is exactly synonymous with anterior megalophthalmos and congenital anterior megalophthalmia.

Meier-Gorlin syndrome is a type of syndrome that is defined as a syndrome characterized by bilateral underdevelopment of the external ear, short stature, absent or underdeveloped patellae, and severe prenatal and postnatal growth retardation. It is also exactly synonymous with ear-patella-short stature syndrome.

Autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder is a type of autosomal dominant disease, intellectual disability, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an intellectual disability characterized by an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern. Furthermore, autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder is exactly synonymous with autosomal dominant mental retardation and autosomal dominant non-syndromic mental retardation.

Autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder is a type of autosomal recessive disease, intellectual disability, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with autosomal recessive mental retardation and autosomal recessive non-syndromic mental retardation.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability is a type of syndromic intellectual disability, a type of X-linked monogenic disease, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. It is defined as a syndromic intellectual disability characterized by an X-linked inheritance pattern and has the exact synonym "syndromic X-linked mental retardation."
Uvulitis is a type of upper respiratory tract disease that is characterized by the swelling of the uvula to 3-5 times its normal size. It is also known exactly as acute uvulitis.

Adenoid hypertrophy is a type of upper respiratory tract disease and is something that at least one disease features, characterized by the unusual growth of the adenoid tonsil. This condition is associated with several symptoms including snoring, hyponasality, otitis media with effusion, and mouth breathing. It is also known by its exact synonyms, adenoidal hypertrophy and enlarged adenoids.

Angular cheilitis is a type of cheilitis and also a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some inflammation. It is characterized by the inflammation of one or both of the corners of the mouth. Angular cheilitis is precisely known by several synonyms, including angular cheilosis, angular stomatitis, cheilosis, and commissural cheilitis.

Tracheomalacia is a type of tracheal disease and also a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some flaccidity. It is defined as a tracheal disease characterized by flaccidity of the tracheal support cartilage. Additionally, tracheomalacia has an exact synonym: congenital tracheomalacia.

Persistent generalized lymphadenopathy is a type of lymph node disease characterized by enlarged, non-painful lymph nodes occurring for more than three to six months for which no other reason can be found. It has the exact synonym PGL.

Oral hairy leukoplakia is a type of mouth disease characterized by a white patch on the side of the tongue with a corrugated or hairy appearance; it is caused by the Epstein-Barr virus. It also has the exact synonym "hairy leukoplakia."

Orofaciodigital syndrome I, also known exactly as Papillon-Leage-Psaume syndrome, orofaciodigital syndrome 1, and orofaciodigital syndrome type I, is a type of orofaciodigital syndrome and an X-linked dominant disease. It is characterized by malformations of the face, oral cavity, and digits, with its material basis in the X-linked dominant inheritance of the OFD1 gene, which results in lethality in males and is associated with polycystic kidney disease. This condition is a manifestation of something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance.

Lung abscess is a type of lung disease and is also a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some necrosis. It is defined as a lung disease characterized by microbial infection which leads to a type of liquefactive necrosis of the pulmonary tissue and results in the formation of cavities containing necrotic debris or fluid.

Acute promyelocytic leukemia is a type of acute myeloid leukemia characterized by the accumulation of promyelocytes in the bone marrow and a translocation between chromosomes 15 and 17. It has several exact synonyms, including acute myeloblastic leukemia type 3, acute myeloblastic leukaemia type 3, acute myeloid leukaemia M3, acute myeloid leukemia M3, and acute promyelocytic leukaemia.

Cardiac arrest is a type of congestive heart failure, and also a type of condition that, at the very least, presents with some symptoms of heart failure. It is defined as a congestive heart failure characterized by a sudden stop in effective blood circulation due to the heart's failure to contract effectively or at all. Furthermore, cardiac arrest is exactly synonymous with both cardiopulmonary arrest and circulatory arrest.
An inguinal hernia is a type of intestinal disease that is defined as a condition characterized by the protrusion of abdominal cavity contents through the inguinal canal.
An umbilical hernia is a type of intestinal disease characterized by the protrusion of part of the intestine through an opening in the abdominal muscles.

Mastoiditis is a type of disease that affects the bone, specifically the middle ear, and is characterized by the inflammation of the mucosal lining of the mastoid antrum and the mastoid air cell system within the mastoid process. This condition is also noted for occurring in locations that at least encompass the middle ear.
A breast abscess is a type of breast disease, which is characterized by a collection of pus in the breast.
A dental abscess is a type of tooth disease, defined as a tooth disease characterized by a localized collection of pus associated with a tooth.
A cervical polyp is a type of cervix disease characterized by a benign polyp on the surface of the cervical canal.

Myelomeningocele is a type of spina bifida, a type of spinal cord disease, and a type of condition that has a location in the spinal cord. It is defined as a spina bifida characterized by the protrusion of the spinal cord through an opening, which is covered by meningeal membranes.

Omphalocele is a type of physical disorder defined as a physical disorder characterized by a defect in the development of the abdominal wall muscles, resulting in the intestines, liver, and other organs remaining outside of the abdomen in a sac. Additionally, omphalocele has an exact synonym, omphalocoele.

An anal fistula is a type of rectal disease which is characterized as an abnormal connection between the epithelialised surface of the anal canal and the perianal skin, defining it as a disease of the anus.
Ectopic pregnancy is a type of female reproductive system disease characterized by the implantation of the embryo outside the uterine cavity. It has an exact synonym, eccyesis.

Rapp-Hodgkin syndrome (RHS) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the category of ectodermal dysplasia. It has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by abnormal development of ectodermal tissues including the skin, hair, nails, teeth, and sweat glands, as well as anhidrotic ectodermal dysplasia with cleft lip/palate. In addition to RHS, this syndrome is exactly synonymous with anhidrotic ectodermal dysplasia with cleft lip/palate, ectodermal dysplasia syndrome, Rapp-Hodgkin type, and ectodermal dysplasia, Rapp-Hodgkin type.

Mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency nuclear type 2 is a specific type of mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency, which is categorized as a disease that fundamentally arises from some structural variant. This particular condition, also exactly known as MC5DN2 or neonatal mitochondrial encephalocardiomyopathy due to ATP synthase deficiency, is defined by a mutation in the TMEM70 gene located on chromosome 8q21.

Mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency nuclear type 3, also known exactly as MC5DN3, is a specific type of mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency. It is characterized as a condition that has its basis in some structural variant, essentially making it a type of disease. The definition of mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency nuclear type 3 includes it being a mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency that has its material basis in a mutation in the ATP5E gene located on chromosome 20q13.

Mitochondrial Complex V ATP Synthase Deficiency Nuclear Type 4, which has the exact synonym MC5DN4, is a specific form of Mitochondrial Complex V ATP Synthase Deficiency. This deficiency is characterized as a type of condition that fundamentally arises from some structural variant. More precisely, the deficiency is defined by a material basis involving a mutation in the ATP5F1A gene located on chromosome 18q21.1.

Transient neonatal diabetes mellitus is a type of neonatal diabetes, defined as a neonatal diabetes that is characterized by hyperglycemia during the neonatal period. This condition remits during infancy but recurs in later life in most patients.

Autosomal dominant sideroblastic anemia 4 is a type of disease that falls under the categories of autosomal dominant disease, sideroblastic anemia, and any condition that fundamentally has an autosomal dominant inheritance as its basis. It is defined as a sideroblastic anemia characterized by an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern.
3-methylglutaconic aciduria is a type of organic acidemia, which is defined as an organic acidemia characterized by elevated levels of 3-methylglutaconic acid and 3-methylglutaric acid in the urine.

Cednik syndrome is a type of syndrome that is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease and relates to conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a syndrome that arises from a homozygous mutation in the SNAP29 gene, characterized by a unique constellation of clinical manifestations including microcephaly, severe neurologic impairment, psychomotor retardation, failure to thrive, facial dysmorphism, palmoplantar keratoderma, and late-onset ichthyosis. Cednik syndrome also has an exact synonym: cerebral dysgenesis, neuropathy, ichthyosis, and keratoderma syndrome.
Parameningeal embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma is a type of embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma that is defined as an embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma located in the parameningeal region.

Chronic Atrial and Intestinal Dysrhythmia (CAID) syndrome is a unique condition characterized by a combination of cardiac arrhythmias and intestinal pseudo-obstruction. It is caused by mutations in the SGOL1 protein. The syndrome presents with distinctive clinical features such as atrial dysrhythmias, sick sinus syndrome (SSS), valve anomalies, and chronic intestinal pseudo-obstruction (CIPO). Additionally, CAID syndrome is an exact synonym for chronic atrial and intestinal dysrhythmia.

Ciliopathy is a type of monogenic disease, a syndrome, and something that has its basis in some gene. It is defined as a syndrome associated with mutations encoding defective proteins, which result in either abnormal formation or function of cilia.

Agnathia otocephaly complex is identified as a type of physical disorder, which is precisely defined as a physical disorder characterized by mandibular hypoplasia or agnathia, ventromedial auricular malposition (melotia) and/or auricular fusion (synotia), and microstomia with oroglossal hypoplasia or aglossia. It is noted that holoprosencephaly is the most commonly identified association with this disorder, but there have also been reports of skeletal, genitourinary, cardiovascular anomalies, and situs inversus. Additionally, this complex is synonymous with several terms, including agnathia-holoprosencephaly-situs inversus syndrome, dysgnathia complex agnathia-holoprosencephaly, holoprosencephaly-agnathia, and otocephaly.

Acromelic frontonasal dysostosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of dysostosis, which is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a dysostosis characterized by cranium bifidum, severe hypertelorism, median cleft lip and palate, nasal bifurcation, brachycephaly, large fontanelle, tibial hemimelia, preaxial polydactyly of the feet, and brain malformations.

Glucocorticoid induced osteoporosis is a type of osteoporosis that also qualifies as a type of condition characterized by at least some ptosis as a symptom. It is defined as an osteoporosis caused by chronic glucocorticoid use, where glucocorticoids impair the replication, differentiation, and function of osteoblasts and induce the apoptosis of mature osteoblasts and osteocytes; they also favor osteoclastogenesis, leading to an increase in bone resorption. Furthermore, it has an exact synonym: steroid-induced osteoporosis.

Acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans is a type of acrodermatitis and is defined as an acrodermatitis characterized by a chronically progressive course, leading to widespread atrophy of the skin. It is a clinical manifestation of Lyme borreliosis. Furthermore, acrodermatitis chronica atrophicans is exactly synonymous with Herxheimer disease and primary diffuse atrophy.

Bacillary angiomatosis is a type of bartonellosis defined as a bartonellosis that has a material basis in either Bartonella henselae or Bartonella quintana. This disease is characterized by the proliferation of blood vessels, leading to the formation of tumor-like masses in the skin and other organs.

Native American myopathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease, congenital myopathy, and is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It exhibits symptoms including muscle weakness and ptosis. This condition is defined as a congenital myopathy that is distinguished by congenital weakness, arthrogryposis, cleft palate, ptosis, myopathic facies, short stature, kyphoscoliosis, talipes deformities, and a susceptibility to malignant hyperthermia provoked by anesthesia. The condition results from a homozygous mutation in the STAC3 gene on chromosome 12q13. Native American myopathy is also known by its exact synonyms, Bailey-Bloch congenital myopathy and congenital myopathy 13.

Acrorenal syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. The syndrome is defined by limb defects that are usually bilateral, such as cleft hands or feet, and longitudinal defects involving the radius or ulna, tibia or fibula, along with renal anomalies including agenesis, hypoplasia, and, though rarely, polycystic kidneys. Additional malformations may involve the oro-mandibular region, the trachea and lungs, skin derivatives including sweat glands, mammary glands, the uterus, vas deferens, the nasal placodes, and the eyes.

Hypoparathyroidism retardation dysmorphism syndrome is a type of syndrome that is specifically an autosomal recessive disease, indicating that it has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by permanent parathyroid hormone (PTH) deficiency, hypocalcemia, hyperphosphatemia, facial anomalies, and psychomotor retardation, which arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TBCE gene on chromosome 1q42.3. Additionally, this syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including HRD syndrome, Sanjad-Sakati syndrome, and hypoparathyroidism with short stature, mental retardation, and seizures.

Microcephaly with or without chorioretinopathy, lymphedema, or mental retardation is a syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases and is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by variable expression of microcephaly, ocular disorders including chorioretinopathy, congenital lymphedema of the lower limbs, and mild to moderate intellectual disability. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms including chorioretinal dysplasia-microcephaly-mental retardation syndrome, lymphedema and retinal folds with microcephaly and microphthalmos, lymphedema, microcephaly and chorioretinopathy syndrome, microcephaly lymphedema chorioretinal dysplasia, and microcephaly, lymphedema, chorioretinal dysplasia syndrome.

Adenine phosphoribosyltransferase (APRT) deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also classified as a purine-pyrimidine metabolic disorder. This condition, having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, is characterized by the formation of 2,8-dihydroxyadenine stones, leading to renal failure secondary to intratubular crystalline precipitation. The disorder is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene encoding adenine phosphoribosyltransferase (APRT) on chromosome 16q24. Furthermore, APRT deficiency is exactly synonymous with 2,8-dihydroxyadenine urolithiasis and is also referred to as APRT deficiency.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency nuclear type 2 (MC3DN2) is a form of mitochondrial complex III deficiency. It is categorized as a type of disease that arises from some structural variant. The condition is defined as a mitochondrial metabolism disease characterized by motor disability, which includes symptoms such as ataxia, apraxia, dystonia, and dysarthria, and is associated with necrotic lesions throughout the brain. The disease is caused by a mutation in the TTC19 gene on chromosome 17 and follows an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern.

Kleefstra syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, chromosomal deletion syndrome, and Kleefstra syndrome. It is characterized by an intersection of conditions that have a material basis in some deletion and chromosome, specifically in autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined by severe mental retardation, hypotonia, microcephaly, epileptic seizures, a flat face with hypertelorism, synophrys, anteverted nares, an everted lower lip, a carp mouth with macroglossia, and heart defects. Its material basis lies in a microdeletion in the chromosome region 9q34.3 or by a point mutation in the EHMT1 gene located in that region. Additionally, Kleefstra syndrome 1 is also known as 9q subtelomeric deletion syndrome, 9q-syndrome, and 9q34 deletion syndrome.

Acrofacial dysostosis Cincinnati type is a type of autosomal dominant disease and acrofacial dysostosis. It is characterized by a spectrum of mandibulofacial dysostosis phenotypes, including cleft palate, micrognathia, malar flattening, microcephaly, and, in some cases, extrafacial skeletal defects. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the POLR1A gene on chromosome 2p11. Additionally, it is associated with phenotypes such as malar flattening and micrognathia, indicating that it at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Stormorken syndrome is a type of disease that is categorized as an autosomal dominant disease, a blood platelet disease, and is characterized by having material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a blood platelet disease characterized by thrombocytopathy, thrombocytopenia, mild anemia, asplenia, tubular aggregate myopathy, miosis, headache, and ichthyosis, and is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the STM1 gene located on chromosome 11p15. Furthermore, it follows an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern and is exactly synonymous with thrombocytopathy, asplenia, and miosis.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 22 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has its material basis in a mutation in the TUBA4A gene on chromosome 2q35. It is exactly synonymous with ALS 22, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 22, and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 22 with or without frontotemporal dementia.

Vici syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by callosal agenesis, cataracts, cardiomyopathy, combined immunodeficiency, and hypopigmentation, with its material basis in a mutation in the EPG5 gene on chromosome 18q12.3. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: immunodeficiency with cleft lip/palate, cataract, hypopigmentation, and absent corpus callosum.

Chylomicron retention disease is a type of lipid metabolism disorder, which is also known as Anderson disease or CMRD. It is a condition with its basis in some structural variant, specifically characterized by malnutrition, failure to thrive, growth failure, vitamin E deficiency, and the absence of chylomicrons and apolipoprotein B48 post-prandially. This disorder follows an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern and is caused by mutations in the SAR1B gene located on chromosome 5q31.1.

Multiple acyl-CoA dehydrogenase deficiency (MADD) is recognized under several exact synonyms, including MAD deficiency, electron transfer flavoprotein deficiency, electron transfer flavoprotein ubiquinone oxidoreductase deficiency, glutaric acidemia type 2, and glutaric aciduria type 2. It is classified as an inherited metabolic disorder and also falls under the categories of disorders with abnormal metabolism phenotypes and diseases with a basis in structural variants. The disorder is defined as an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by the body's inability to break down proteins and fats to produce energy, involving a disruption in fatty acid, amino acid, and choline metabolism. This condition follows an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern and is caused by mutations in the ETFA, ETFB, and ETFDH genes. MADD presents three clinical phenotypes: a neonatal-onset form with congenital anomalies (type I), a neonatal-onset form without congenital anomalies (type II), and a late-onset form (type III), with the neonatal-onset forms usually being fatal.

Sakati Nyhan syndrome is a type of acrocephalosyndactylia characterized by abnormalities in the bones of the legs, congenital heart defects, craniofacial defects, and craniosynostosis. Patients with this condition suffer from cyanosis and other respiratory and breathing infections. Sakati Nyhan syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including ACPS with leg hypoplasia, Sakati syndrome, Sakati-Nyhan-Tisdale syndrome, acrocephalopolysyndactyly Type III, and acrocephalopolysyndactyly type 3.

Hereditary papulotranslucent acrokeratoderma is a type of cholesteatoma and also a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some papule. It is defined as a keratosis of the hands and feet characterized by persistent, asymptomatic, yellowish to white papules and plaques, associated with fine-textured scalp hair, and an atopic diathesis.

Punctate palmoplantar keratoderma is a type of palmoplantar keratosis characterized by keratoses with a raindrop pattern on the palmoplantar surface. These skin lesions may involve the entire palmoplantar surface or may be more restricted in their distribution. It is also known exactly as punctate palmoplantar hyperkeratosis and is relatedly referred to as punctate keratosis palmoplantaris.

Punctate palmoplantar keratoderma type III is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a subtype of punctate palmoplantar keratoderma. It is characterized by the hyperkeratinization of the palms and soles, which has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically due to a mutation in the AAGAB gene. This condition is precisely known by several synonyms, including acrokeratoelastoidosis of Costa, punctate palmoplantar hyperkeratosis type 3, and punctate palmoplantar keratoderma type 3.

Glycerol kinase deficiency is an inherited metabolic disorder, which is a type of condition that has its basis in some structural variant. It is defined as an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by a wide range of phenotypic variability. Patients can have severe metabolic and central nervous system (CNS) abnormalities, while others may have hyperglycerolemia and glyceroluria with no other apparent phenotype. The disorder has its material basis in a mutation in the GK gene located on chromosome Xp21.

Galloway Mowat Syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it is specifically a form of Galloway Mowat Syndrome. It has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and is defined by a homozygous mutation in the WDR73 gene on chromosome 15q25. Galloway Mowat Syndrome 1 is known by several exact synonyms, including Galloway Syndrome, SCAR5, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 5, microcephaly, hiatal hernia and nephrotic syndrome, nephrosis-microcephaly syndrome, and nephrosis-neuronal dysmigration syndrome.

Mandibulofacial dysostosis with alopecia is a type of syndrome characterized by malar and mandibular hypoplasia, typically associated with abnormalities of the ears and eyelids, and with alopecia. It is also exactly known as MFDA.

Hennekam syndrome is a type of lymphatic system disease characterized by the presence of intestinal lymphangiectasia, mental retardation, and characteristic facial anomalies, inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern. Most individuals with Hennekam syndrome exhibit facial abnormalities such as a flat face with puffy eyelids and hypertelorism, a typically flat nasal bridge, and small ears. Congenital extremity and genital lymphedema is present in most patients. This condition is also known by its exact synonyms, Hennekam lymphangiectasia-lymphedema syndrome and lymphedema-lymphangiectasia-intellectual disability syndrome.

Parkinson's disease 1 is an autosomal dominant form of Parkinson's disease and also a late-onset type. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically due to a mutation in the alpha-synuclein gene located on chromosome 4q22.1. Additionally, Parkinson's disease 1 is exactly synonymous with autosomal dominant Parkinson disease 1 and autosomal dominant Parkinson's disease 1.

Parkinson's Disease 2 is characterized by several aspects. It is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is classified as an early-onset Parkinson's Disease, stemming from its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as an early-onset Parkinson's Disease that originates from a mutation in the parkin gene located on chromosome 6q25.2-q27. Additionally, Parkinson's Disease 2 is synonymously known as autosomal recessive juvenile Parkinson Disease 2.

Parkinson's disease 6 is characterized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, early-onset Parkinson's disease, and digenic disease. It specifically has a material basis in autosomal recessive and digenic inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as an early-onset Parkinson's disease that occurs due to mutations in the PINK1 gene on chromosome 1p36.12. The disease is also known by its exact synonyms: PARK6, autosomal recessive early-onset Parkinson disease 6, autosomal recessive early-onset Parkinson's disease 6, and early-onset Parkinson disease 6.

Parkinson's disease 7 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and an early-onset Parkinson's disease, which is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as an early-onset Parkinson's disease that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DJ1 gene on chromosome 1p36. Furthermore, Parkinson's disease 7 is precisely referred to as autosomal recessive early-onset Parkinson disease 7, and also known as autosomal recessive early-onset Parkinson's disease 7.

Parkinson's disease 8 is a type of autosomal dominant and late-onset Parkinson's disease, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a late-onset Parkinson's disease that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the dardarin encoding gene located on chromosome 12q12. Moreover, Parkinson's disease 8 is exactly synonymous with both autosomal dominant Parkinson disease 8 and autosomal dominant Parkinson's disease 8.

Parkinson's disease 15 is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease, specifically an early-onset Parkinson's disease, and is associated with material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an early-onset Parkinson's disease that originates from a mutation in the FBXO7 gene located on chromosome 22q12.3. This condition is precisely known by several synonyms, including Parkinsonian-pyramidal syndrome, autosomal recessive early-onset Parkinson disease 15, autosomal recessive early-onset Parkinson's disease 15, and pallidopyramidal syndrome.

Orofaciodigital syndrome III, also known exactly as Sugarman syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of orofaciodigital syndrome. It is characterized by dysmorphic facies and severe intellectual deficits. This syndrome has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance, indicating that it at least partially arises from this type of genetic transmission.

Orofaciodigital syndrome IV, also known precisely as Baraitser-Burn syndrome or OFD4, is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and is categorized under orofaciodigital syndromes. This syndrome arises fundamentally from autosomal recessive inheritance, particularly due to mutations in the TCTN3 gene. It is characterized by distinct facial features, the formation of harmartomas on the tongue, polydactyly, and limb dysplasia.

Orofaciodigital syndrome V is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader category of orofaciodigital syndromes. It is characterized by a type of autosomal recessive inheritance with a material basis in some instances. Specifically, this syndrome is characterized by postaxial polydactyly and median cleft of the upper lip, caused by a homozygous mutation in the DDX59 gene on chromosome 1q32. Moreover, orofaciodigital syndrome V is also known by its exact synonyms: OFD5, orofaciodigital syndrome Thurston type, and polydactyly, postaxial, with median cleft of upper lip.

Joubert syndrome with orofaciodigital defect is a type of Joubert syndrome that is characterized by an orofaciodigital defect. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms, including OFD6, Polydactyly cleft lip palate psychomotor retardation, Varadi syndrome, Varadi-Papp syndrome, and orofaciodigital syndrome VI.

Orofaciodigital syndrome VII, also known by its exact synonyms OFD7 and Whelan syndrome, is a type of orofaciodigital syndrome. It is characterized by oral, facial, and digital abnormalities and has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Orofaciodigital syndrome VIII, also known exactly as Edwards syndrome or OFD8, is a specific type of Orofaciodigital syndrome and a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that, at a minimum, has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance, including features such as tongue lobulation, hypoplasia of the epiglottis, cleft lip, polydactyly, short stature, and intellectual deficit.

Acrofacial dysostosis is a type of dysostosis with a definition as a heterogeneous dysostosis characterized by digital dysplasia, downslanted palpebral fissures, deafness, and developmental delay. It has a material basis in mutation to the SF3B4 gene.

Orofaciodigital syndrome X, which has the exact synonyms OFD10 and orofaciodigital syndrome with fibular aplasia, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific instance of orofaciodigital syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Moreover, it is defined as an orofaciodigital syndrome marked by facial, oral, and digital deformities, in addition to radial shortening, fibular agenesis, and the coalescence of tarsal bones.

Orofaciodigital syndrome XI is a type of orofaciodigital syndrome that is defined by its distinctive characteristics, which include blepharophimosis, a bulbous nasal tip, a broad nasal bridge, downslanting palpebral fissures, low-set ears, skeletal malformations, intellectual deficits, deafness, and congenital heart defects.

Orofaciodigital syndrome IX, which has exact synonyms OFD9 and orofaciodigital syndrome with retinal abnormalities, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific instance of orofaciodigital syndrome. It is defined as an orofaciodigital syndrome characterized by a highly arched palate with a bifid tongue, harmartomatous tongue, hypertelorism, telecanthus, strabismus, a bifid nasal tip, short stature, bifid halluces, a forked metatarsal, polydactyly, mild intellectual deficit, and specific retinal abnormalities. Its material basis is rooted in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Acrofacial dysostosis Rodriguez type is a specific variety of acrofacial dysostosis. It is defined by its characteristics, which include CNS malformations, lung anomalies, congenital heart defects, dysmorphic facies, and limb reduction, and it arises through autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with acrofacial dysostosis, syndrome of Rodriguez.

Acrofacial dysostosis Catania type is a type of acrofacial dysostosis, and it is defined by an acrofacial dysostosis characterized by intrauterine growth retardation, short stature, microcephaly, cleft palate, limb hypoplasia, simian creases, and cryptorchidism/hypospadias. This condition also has exact synonyms, including Opitz Mollica Sorge syndrome and Opitz-Caltabiano syndrome.

Acrofacial dysostosis Patagonia type is a type of acrofacial dysostosis. It is defined as an acrofacial dysostosis characterized by oligodontia, short stature, pili torti, syndactyly, vertebral abnormalities, and cleft lip. This condition has a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance.

Chilblain lupus is a type of cutaneous lupus erythematosus and is defined as a cutaneous form of systemic lupus erythematosus. It is characterized by painful nodular skin lesions precipitated by variation in temperatures and has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of mutation in the TREX1 gene.

Chondrodysplasia Blomstrand type is a type of osteochondrodysplasia and has an exact synonym, Blomstrand lethal chondrodysplasia. It is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia that is characterized by rapid endochondral bone maturation, short limbs, dwarfism, and prenatal lethality. This condition has a material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the PTH1R gene.

Chromosomal deletion syndrome is the same as a condition that lies at the intersection of a disease and something that at least has a material basis in some deletion and something that at least has a material basis in some chromosome. It is a type of chromosomal disease. Moreover, chromosomal deletion syndrome is defined as a chromosomal disease that has its material basis in the partial deletion of chromosomes.

Chromosome 10q23 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by dysmorphic facies, developmental delay, multiple congenital abnormalities, and juvenile polyposis. It has a material basis in recurrent deletions of chromosome 10q22.3-q23.2.

Distal 10q deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome that is characterized by developmental delay, intellectual disability, behavioral problems, and facial facies caused by a missing copy of the long arm of chromosome 10. It is also known by exact synonyms including chromosome 10q26 deletion syndrome, distal monosomy 10q, monosomy 10qter, telomeric deletion 10q, and terminal chromosome 10q26 deletion syndrome.

Chromosome 13q14 deletion syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that, at the very least, has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by low birth weight, dysmorphic facies, limb defects, genital malformations, and psychomotor developmental delay, with its material basis in the deletion of the long arm of chromosome 13. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with deletion 13q14.

Chromosome 14q11 q22 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome that is defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by microcephaly, dysmorphic facies, psychomotor delay, and failure to thrive. It has a material basis in isolated cases of partial deletion of the long arm of chromosome 14. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: 14q11.2 microdeletion syndrome.

Chromosome 15q11.2 deletion syndrome, also known as 15q11.2 microdeletion syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant and chromosomal deletion syndrome. It is characterized by intellectual disability, dysmorphic facies, psychiatric illness, and autism spectrum disorder. This syndrome has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically stemming from the partial deletion of the long arm of chromosome 15.

Chromosome 15q13.3 microdeletion syndrome, also known exactly as 15q13.3 microdeletion syndrome, is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome. It is defined by a range of characteristics including intellectual disability, developmental delay, autism spectrum disorder, and seizures. These symptoms result from the autosomal dominant inheritance of a partial deletion of the long arm of chromosome 15.

Chromosome 15q24 deletion syndrome, also known as 15q24 microdeletion syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome. It is characterized by dysmorphic facial features, intellectual disability, and seizure. This syndrome has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically due to a mutation in the SIN3A gene causing a partial deletion of the long arm of chromosome 15.

Chromosome 15q25 deletion syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant and chromosomal deletion syndrome, which specifically has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by intellectual disability and developmental delay, with its material basis in the partial deletion of the long arm of chromosome 15.

Chromosome 15q26 qter deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome that is characterized by pre- and postnatal growth restriction, developmental delay, variable degrees of intellectual disability, brachy-clinodactyly, talipes equinovarus, nail hypoplasia, proximally placed digits, and mild craniofacial dysmorphism including microcephaly, triangular face, broad nasal bridge, and micrognathia. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including 15q26 deletion syndrome, Drayer syndrome, distal 15q deletion syndrome, distal monosomy 15q, and telomeric 15q deletion syndrome.

Chromosome 16p11.2 deletion syndrome 220 kb is a chromosomal deletion syndrome defined by a partial deletion of the short arm of chromosome 16, specifically a deletion of a 220-kb region on chromosome 16p11.2 (chr16:28.73-28.95 Mb) that encompasses approximately 9 genes, including the SH2B1 gene. This syndrome is characterized by developmental delay, mild intellectual disability, and autism spectrum disorder. It is also known by the exact synonym distal 16p11.2 microdeletion syndrome. Chromosome 16p11.2 deletion syndrome 220 kb is classified under a broader match of ICD10CM:Q93.5 and has exact matches with several medical identifiers: OMIM:613444, ORDO:261222, and UMLS_CUI codes C3150701 and C4518824.

Chromosome 16p12.1 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome. It is defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome that is based on a 520 kb deletion on the short (p) arm of the chromosome at a location designated 16p12.1. This syndrome is characterized by developmental delay, craniofacial dysmorphology, and congenital heart defects.

Chromosome 16p12.2-p11.2 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome defined by a chromosome 16p12.2-p11.2 deletion. This syndrome is characterized by dysmorphic facial features, feeding difficulties, recurrent ear infections, developmental delay, and cognitive impairment. It is also known by the exact synonyms 16p11.2-p12.2 microdeletion syndrome and 16p11.2p12.2 microdeletion syndrome.

Chromosome 16q22 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome defined by an interstitial 16q22 deletion. It is characterized by a failure to thrive in infancy, poor growth, delayed psychomotor development, hypotonia, and dysmorphic features. These features include a large anterior fontanel, high forehead, diastasis of the cranial sutures, broad nasal bridge, hypertelorism, low-set abnormal ears, and a short neck.

Chromosome 17p13.1 deletion syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, chromosomal deletion syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome that has a material basis in a chromosome 17p13.1 deletion and is characterized by mild global developmental delay/intellectual disability with poor to absent speech, dysmorphic features including a long midface, retrognathia with overbite, protruding ears, microcephaly, failure to thrive, wide-based gait, and a body posture with knee and elbow flexion with hands held in a midline.

Chromosome 17q11.2 deletion syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is also categorized under chromosomal deletion syndromes. This condition stems from an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern. It is defined by a contiguous gene deletion on 17q11.2 that encompasses the NF1 gene. Furthermore, Chromosome 17q11.2 deletion syndrome is known by various exact synonyms, including 17q11 microdeletion syndrome, NF1 microdeletion syndrome, Van Asperen syndrome, and neurofibromatosis type 1 microdeletion syndrome.

Chromosome 17q12 deletion syndrome, also known exactly as 17q12 microdeletion syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and chromosomal deletion syndrome. It specifically has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined by a chromosomal deletion in chromosome 17q12 and characterized by various conditions including renal cystic disease, maturity onset diabetes of the young type 5, cognitive impairment, developmental delay (particularly of speech), autistic traits, and autism spectrum disorder.

Chromosome 17q23.1-q23.2 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome with a definition that specifies it is caused by a deletion in chromosome 17q23.1-q23.2. This syndrome is characterized by developmental delay, microcephaly, short stature, heart defects, and limb abnormalities. It is also exactly synonymous with 17q23.1-q23.2 microdeletion syndrome and 17q23.1q23.2 microdeletion syndrome.

Chromosome 18p deletion syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and chromosomal deletion syndrome, which is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome that results from the partial or complete deletion of the short arm of chromosome 18. This condition is also exactly synonymous with 18p- syndrome, De Grouchy syndrome, and monosomy 18p.

Chromosome 18q deletion syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, chromosomal deletion syndrome, and something that has at least a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome that is based on a terminal deficiency or macrodeletion characterized by mental retardation and congenital malformations. Furthermore, chromosome 18q deletion syndrome is exactly synonymous with 18q- syndrome, deletion 18q, and monosomy 18q.

Chromosome 19q13 11 deletion syndrome, also known precisely as 19q13.11 microdeletion syndrome and monosomy 19q13.11, is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, which is categorized under autosomal dominant diseases. It is a condition that fundamentally arises from an autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined by a chromosomal deletion specifically in chromosome 19q13.11, characterized by a combination of symptoms including poor overall growth, slender habitus, microcephaly, delayed development, intellectual disability with poor or absent speech, and feeding difficulties.

NFIA related disorder is a type of autosomal dominant disease, chromosomal deletion syndrome, and syndrome. It is characterized by being an intersection of conditions that at least have a material basis in some deletion and chromosome, as well as having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The disorder is defined as a syndrome that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the NFIA gene on chromosome 1p31, characterized by macrocephaly, seizures, developmental delay, dysmorphic features, ventriculomegaly, and hypotonia. Furthermore, NFIA related disorder is exactly synonymous with 1p31p32 microdeletion syndrome, Chromosome 1, Monosomy 1p32, brain malformations with or without urinary tract defects, and chromosome 1p32-p31 deletion syndrome.

Chromosome 1p36 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome defined by a deletion of the chromosome 1p36 region. It is characterized by severe intellectual disability, a small head, deep-set eyes with straight eyebrows, midface hypoplasia, a broad, flat nose, a pointed chin, and low-set ears. This condition is also exactly known as 1p36 deletion syndrome, deletion 1p36, and monosomy 1p36. Furthermore, it is relatedly referred to as subtelomeric 1p36 deletion.

Chromosome 1q21.1 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome defined by a contiguous deletion of the 1q21.1 region on chromosome 1. This condition is characterized by an increased risk of delayed development, intellectual disability, physical abnormalities, and neurological and psychiatric problems. It is also exactly synonymous with 1q21.1 microdeletion syndrome and is relatedly referred to as monosomy 1q21.1.

Chromosome 1q41 q42 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome that has its material basis in the deletion of the chromosome 1q41-q42 region. It is also exactly synonymous with 1q41-q42 microdeletion syndrome and 1q41q42 microdeletion syndrome.

Chromosome 22q11.2 deletion syndrome distal is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, which is defined by a deletion of the chromosome 22q11.2 region. This definition specifies that it is distinct from DiGeorge syndrome and velocardiofacial syndrome. However, it also has exact synonyms, including 22q11.2 deletion syndrome, DiGeorge syndrome, Velocardiofacial syndrome, and distal 22q11.2 microdeletion syndrome.

Chromosome 2p12 p11 2 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome that has its material basis in the deletion of the chromosome 2p12-p11.2 region.

Chromosome 2p16.1-p15 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome defined by a deletion of the chromosome 2p16.1-p15 region. It is characterized by delayed psychomotor development, intellectual disability, and variable but distinctive dysmorphic features, including microcephaly, bitemporal narrowing, smooth and long philtrum, hypertelorism, downslanting palpebral fissures, broad nasal root, thin upper lip, and high palate. This syndrome is also exactly known as the 2p15p16.1 microdeletion syndrome and is relatedly referred to as the 2p15-p16.1 microdeletion syndrome.

Chromosome 2q31.2 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by a chromosomal deletion syndrome that has its material basis in the deletion of the chromosome 2q31.2 region.

3p deletion syndrome, also known as chromosome 3pter-P25 deletion syndrome or distal monosomy 3p, is a type of autosomal dominant and chromosomal deletion syndrome. It has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is characterized by symptoms such as ptosis. The syndrome's definition highlights it as a chromosomal deletion syndrome with its material basis in a contiguous gene deletion syndrome involving chromosome 3pter-p25. It is characterized by a spectrum of features including low birth weight, microcephaly, trigonocephaly, hypotonia, psychomotor and growth retardation, telecanthus, downslanting palpebral fissures, and micrognathia.

Chromosome 3q13.31 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome that is characterized by a marked developmental delay, characteristic facies with a short philtrum and protruding lips, and abnormal male genitalia. This condition has its material basis in the deletion of the chromosome 3q13.31 region. It is also exactly known as 3q13 microdeletion syndrome and monosomy 3q13.

Chromosome 3q29 microdeletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by the deletion of the chromosome 3q29 region. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including 3q subtelomere deletion syndrome, 3q29 microdeletion syndrome, 3q29 recurrent deletion, and 3qter deletion.

Chromosome 4q21 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by the deletion of the chromosome 4q21 region. It is also precisely referred to as 4q21 microdeletion syndrome and monosomy 4q21.

Chromosome 5q12 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome that has its material basis in the deletion of the chromosome 5q12 region.

Chromosome 6pter p24 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, characterized by the deletion of the chromosome 6pter-p24 region. It is also precisely known by several synonyms including 6p subtelomeric deletion syndrome, 6p25 microdeletion syndrome, and distal monosomy 6p.

Chromosome 6q11 q14 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome defined by the deletion of the chromosome 6q11-q14 region. It is characterized by hypotonia, short stature, skeletal/limb anomalies, umbilical hernia, and urinary tract anomalies, alongside distinctive facial features such as upslanting palpebral fissures, low-set and/or dysplastic ears, and a high-arched palate.

Chromosome 6q24 q25 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, defined by a chromosomal deletion syndrome that has its material basis in deletion of the chromosome 6q24-q25 region. This syndrome is also exactly known as 6q25 microdeletion syndrome and monosomy 6q25.

Chromosome 8q21.11 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, which is defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome that has its material basis in the deletion of the chromosome 8q21.11 region. It is characterized by intellectual disability and common facial dysmorphic features. Additionally, this syndrome is exactly synonymous with 8q21.11 microdeletion syndrome.

Chromosome 19p13.13 deletion syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, chromosomal deletion syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome that has a material basis in a chromosome 19p13.13 deletion and is characterized by an unusually large head size, tall stature, and intellectual disability that is usually moderate in severity.

Chromosome Xp21 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, which is defined by the deletion of the chromosome Xp21 region. It is exactly synonymous with Xp21 microdeletion syndrome, complex glycerol kinase deficiency, and monosomy Xp21.

SATB2 associated syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, which is a specific category of syndrome. It falls under an intersection of conditions that have a material basis in some form of deletion and chromosome involvement. This syndrome is defined by genetic changes affecting the SATB2 gene, characterized by mild to severe intellectual disability, a delayed or absent ability to speak, severe speech anomalies, abnormalities of the palate, teeth anomalies, behavioral issues with or without bone or brain anomalies, with onset before age 2. SATB2 associated syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including 2q32-q33 microdeletion syndrome, 2q32q33 microdeletion syndrome, Glass syndrome, chromosome 2q32-q33 deletion syndrome, monosomy 2q32, monosomy 2q32-q33, and monosomy 2q32q33.

Chromosomal duplication syndrome is the same as a disease that intersects with conditions that at least have a material basis in some chromosome and in some duplication. It is a type of chromosomal disease. Additionally, chromosomal duplication syndrome is defined as a chromosomal disease that has its material basis in extra copies of a chromosomal region.

Chromosome 16p11.2 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome defined by a duplication of the chromosome 16p11.2 region. It is characterized by low weight, a small head size, and developmental delay, particularly in speech and language. This condition is also exactly synonymous with proximal 16p11.2 microduplication syndrome, proximal dup(16)(p11.2), and proximal trisomy 16p11.2.

Chromosome 16p13.3 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome defined by the duplication of the chromosome 16p13.3 region. It is also precisely known by several synonyms, including 16p13.3 microduplication syndrome, distal duplication 16p, distal trisomy 16p, and telomeric duplication 16p.

Chromosome 17p13.3 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome, defined by the duplication of the chromosome 17p13.3 region. It is also precisely known by several synonyms including 17p13.3 duplication syndrome, 17p13.3 microduplication syndrome, chromosome 17p13.3 centromeric duplication syndrome, and trisomy 17p13.3.

Chromosome 17q12 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome defined by the duplication of the chromosome 17q12 region. It is also exactly synonymous with 17q12 microduplication syndrome and trisomy 17q12.

Chromosome 17q21.31 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome with a definition that states it is a chromosomal duplication syndrome having its material basis in the duplication of the chromosome 17q21.31 region. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with 17q21.31 microduplication syndrome and trisomy 17q21.31.

Chromosome 1q21.1 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome that is characterized by the duplication of the chromosome 1q21.1 region. It is also exactly known as 1q21.1 microduplication syndrome and trisomy 1q21.1.

Chromosome 22q11.2 microduplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome, defined by the duplication of the chromosome 22q11.2 region. It is also exactly known as 22q11.2 microduplication syndrome, duplication 22q11.2, and trisomy 22q11.2.

Chromosome 22q13 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome characterized by a chromosomal duplication that has a material basis in the duplication of the chromosome 22q13 region.

Cole Carpenter Syndrome is a type of Osteogenesis Imperfecta and is also a type of condition that at least has the symptom of ptosis. It is defined as an Osteogenesis Imperfecta characterized by craniosynostosis, communicating hydrocephalus, ocular proptosis, marked postnatal growth failure, and a distinctive facial appearance.

Lysinuric protein intolerance (LPI) is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by the body's inability to effectively break down lysine, arginine, and ornithine. It results in renal hyperdiaminoaciduria, notably lysinuria, and impaired formation of urea with hyperammonemia after protein ingestion. This condition is also known by its exact synonyms: dibasic amino aciduria II and hyperdibasic aminoaciduria. LPI has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the amino acid transporter gene SLC7A7 on chromosome 14q11. Furthermore, lysinuric protein intolerance is a type of disease that has its basis in some structural variant.
Epithelial and subepithelial dystrophy, which is a type of corneal dystrophy, is defined as a corneal dystrophy that primarily affects the corneal epithelium and its basement membrane.

Epithelial stromal TGFBI dystrophy, a type of corneal dystrophy, is defined as a corneal dystrophy characterized by abnormal deposition of proteins in the cornea, caused by mutations in the TGFBI gene on chromosome 5q.
Stromal dystrophy, which is a type of corneal dystrophy, is defined as a corneal dystrophy that affects the corneal stroma.

Corneal endothelial dystrophy is a type of corneal dystrophy defined as a corneal dystrophy that affects the corneal endothelium and/or the Descemet membrane. It is also exactly synonymous with endothelial dystrophy.

Granular corneal dystrophy 2 is a type of granular corneal dystrophy, which also falls under the category of conditions with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a corneal granular dystrophy characterized by recurrent erosions, stellate or thorn-like opacification located in the cornea, hyaline and amyloid deposits in the stroma, and progressive vision loss later in life. This condition is caused by autosomal dominant inheritance of a mutation of the transforming growth factor beta-induced gene on chromosome 5q31.1, which encodes keratoepithelin. The abnormalities this mutation causes lead to increased hyaline and amyloid protein deposition and disruption of the corneal surface. Granular corneal dystrophy 2 is also known by several exact synonyms, including CGD2, Avellino corneal dystrophy, combined granular-lattice corneal dystrophy, and corneal dystrophy, Avellino type, signifying its diverse nomenclature but singular entity.

Congenital stromal corneal dystrophy (CSCD), also known as congenital hereditary stromal dystrophy, is a type of stromal dystrophy and a physical disorder. It is classified as a condition that has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. CSCD is defined as a stromal dystrophy characterized by the presence of bilateral corneal opacities that can be seen at or shortly after birth.

X-linked endothelial corneal dystrophy is a type of corneal endothelial dystrophy, which is also categorized as an X-linked dominant disease. This condition is based on the material basis of X-linked dominant inheritance. It is defined as a corneal endothelial dystrophy characterized by congenital ground glass corneal clouding or a diffuse corneal haze, and blurred vision in male patients. Additionally, it has the exact synonym XECD.

Epithelial basement membrane dystrophy is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also classified under epithelial and subepithelial dystrophy, indicating its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by sheet-like areas of basement membrane originating from the basal epithelial cells of the corneal epithelium, extending superficially into the epithelium. This condition is precisely known by several exact synonyms, including Cogan corneal dystrophy, EBMD, and microcystic corneal dystrophy.

Fleck corneal dystrophy, which is a type of stromal dystrophy, is defined as a stromal dystrophy characterized by numerous tiny, dot-like white flecks scattered in all layers of the corneal stroma. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PIKFYVE gene on chromosome 2q34. Fleck corneal dystrophy is also exactly synonymous with FCD and Francois-Neetens speckled corneal dystrophy.

Gelatinous drop-like corneal dystrophy (GDCD), also known as corneal amyloidosis, primary familial amyloidosis of the cornea, and subepithelial amyloidosis of the cornea, is an autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of epithelial and subepithelial dystrophy. It specifically arises from a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as an epithelial and subepithelial dystrophy characterized by severe corneal amyloidosis that leads to blindness. It is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TACSTD2 gene, which encodes the monoclonal antibody-defined, tumor-associated antigen GA733-1, located on chromosome 1p32.

Lisch epithelial corneal dystrophy (LECD), also known as band-shaped and whorled microcystic, is a type of epithelial and subepithelial dystrophy. It is also classified as a type of X-linked dominant disease, which means it has a material basis in some form of X-linked dominant inheritance. This condition is defined by its characteristic presentation, which includes bilateral or unilateral, gray, band-shaped, and feathery opacities that sometimes appear in whorled patterns.

Meesmann corneal dystrophy is a type of epithelial and subepithelial dystrophy characterized by the formation of tiny round cysts in the corneal epithelium. It has exact synonyms: MECD, Stocker-Holt dystrophy, and juvenile hereditary epithelial dystrophy.

Posterior amorphous corneal dystrophy (PACD), also known as chromosome 12q21.33 deletion syndrome, is a type of stromal dystrophy. It is characterized by irregular sheetlike areas of opacification that involve the Descemet membrane and, in some cases, alterations of the normal endothelial mosaic. This condition is a result of an autosomal dominant disease and is associated with a chromosomal deletion syndrome. Specifically, PACD has its material basis in a chromosome 12q21.33 contiguous gene deletion syndrome. Moreover, it falls under the category of diseases that have a material basis in both some deletion and some chromosome, particularly those involving autosomal dominant inheritance.

Reis Bucklers corneal dystrophy is a type of epithelial-stromal TGFBI dystrophy, which is defined as an epithelial-stromal TGFBI dystrophy characterized by recurrent erosions and irregular geographic opacification located in the cornea. It also involves proteinaceous deposits in the anterior stroma and subepithelium, leading to progressive early vision loss. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation of the transforming growth factor beta-induced gene located in chromosome 5q31.1, encoding keratoepithelin. The abnormalities result in increased protein deposition and disruption, especially of Bowman's membrane of the cornea. Reis Bucklers corneal dystrophy is also known by several exact synonyms: RBCD, anterior limiting membrane dystrophy type I, corneal dystrophy of Bowman layer type I, geographic corneal dystrophy, and granular corneal dystrophy type III.

Subepithelial mucinous corneal dystrophy, which is a type of epithelial and subepithelial dystrophy, is defined as an epithelial and subepithelial dystrophy characterized by frequent, recurrent corneal erosions in the first decade of life. It also has the exact synonym SMCD.

Thiel Behnke corneal dystrophy, also known exactly as TBCD, Waardenburg-Jonker corneal dystrophy, anterior limiting membrane dystrophy type II, corneal dystrophy honeycomb-shaped, and corneal dystrophy of Bowman layer type II, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically an epithelial stromal TGFBI dystrophy. It is characterized by recurrent erosions and honeycomb-shaped opacification located in the cornea, proteinaceous deposits in the anterior stroma and subepithelium, and progressive early vision loss. This condition has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of heterozygous mutation of the transforming growth factor beta-induced gene located on chromosome 5q31.1, which encodes keratoepithelin. The abnormalities lead to increased protein deposition and disruption, especially of Bowman's membrane of the cornea.

Schnyder corneal dystrophy is a type of autosomal dominant disease and stromal dystrophy, which is specifically characterized as a condition with at least a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a stromal dystrophy characterized by the abnormal deposition of cholesterol and phospholipids in the cornea, a condition resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the UBAID1 gene located on chromosome 1p36. Furthermore, Schnyder corneal dystrophy is known by several exact synonyms including SCCD, Schnyder crystalline corneal dystrophy, corneal dystrophy crystalline of Schnyder, crystalline stromal dystrophy, and hereditary crystalline stromal dystrophy of Schnyder.

Posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy is a type of corneal dystrophy characterized by changes in Descemet's membrane and the endothelial layer. It has exact synonyms such as PPCD, Schlichting dystrophy, and hereditary polymorphus posterior corneal dystrophy.

Chromosome 2q31.1 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome, which is defined by the duplication of the chromosome 2q31.1 region, having its material basis in this specific chromosomal duplication.

Chromosome 3q29 microduplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome, defined as a chromosomal duplication syndrome that has its material basis in the duplication of the chromosome 3q29 region. It is precisely synonymous with 3q29 microduplication and trisomy 3q29.

Chromosome 5p13 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome characterized by a chromosomal duplication syndrome that has its material basis in the duplication of the chromosome 5p13 region. It is also exactly synonymous with 5p13 microduplication syndrome and trisomy 5p13.

Chromosome Xp11.23-p11.22 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome, an X-linked dominant disease, and something that at least has a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. It is defined as a chromosomal duplication syndrome that has a material basis in duplication of the chromosome Xp11.23-p11.22 region. Additionally, this syndrome has exact synonyms, including microduplication Xp11.22-p11.23 syndrome and trisomy Xp11.22-p11.23.

Desbuquois dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by short stature, joint laxity, scoliosis, and advanced carpal ossification with a delta phalanx. It is also known by exact synonyms such as Desbuquois syndrome and micromelic dwarfism with vertebral and metaphyseal abnormalities and advanced carpotarsal ossification.

Nut midline carcinoma is a type of carcinoma characterized by a BRD4-NUT translocation involving the rearrangement of the bromodomain-containing protein 4 (BRD4) and the gene encoding nuclear protein of the testis (NUT) at 15q14, BRD4-NUT t(15;19)(q14;q13.1). This carcinoma arises from midline epithelial structures, most commonly the head, neck, and mediastinum. It also has the exact synonym "nuclear protein in testis midline carcinoma."

Feingold syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by a syndrome that includes variable combinations of microcephaly, limb malformations, esophageal and duodenal atresias, and learning disability/mental retardation. Feingold syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms: FGLDS, MODED syndrome, ODED syndrome, digital anomalies with short palpebral fissures and atresia of esophagus or duodenum, microcephaly-digital anomalies-normal intelligence syndrome, microcephaly-oculo-digito-esophageal-duodenal syndrome, and oculo-digito-esophageal-duodenal syndrome.

Fibrochondrogenesis is a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by shortened long bones in the arms and legs that are unusually wide at the ends, flattened vertebrae with a characteristic pinched or pear shape, and a very narrow chest in infants with short, wide ribs and a round and prominent abdomen.

Gingival fibromatosis is a type of gingival overgrowth and is defined as a gingival overgrowth characterized by benign, slowly progressive, nonhemorrhagic, fibrous enlargement of the oral masticatory mucosa. It has the exact synonyms hereditary gingival fibromatosis and hereditary gingival hyperplasia.

Humeroradial synostosis is a type of synostosis characterized by uni- or bilateral fusion of the humerus and radius bones at the elbow level, which may or may not be associated with ulnar and carpal/metacarpal deficiency. This condition leads to loss of elbow motion and, in many cases, results in functional arm incapacity. It is also related to the synonym humero-radial fusion.

Holt-Oram syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, specifically one that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by congenital anomalies located in the heart and upper limb. Furthermore, Holt-Oram syndrome is also known by exact synonyms including atrio-digital syndrome, atriodigital dysplasia, and heart-hand syndrome.

Miller-Dieker Lissencephaly Syndrome (MDS), also known as Miller-Dieker syndrome, is a type of syndrome, specifically an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by classical lissencephaly and distinct facial features, with its material basis in submicroscopic deletions of 17p13.3, including the LIS1 gene. This syndrome is also described as something that inherently has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Salt and Pepper Syndrome, also known exactly as Salt & Pepper Syndrome and Salt-and-Pepper Syndrome, is a type of syndrome and autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a syndrome that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, Salt and Pepper Syndrome is defined as a syndrome characterized by severe intellectual disability, epilepsy, scoliosis, choreoathetosis, dysmorphic facial features, and altered dermal pigmentation. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SIAT9 gene on chromosome 2p11.2.

Fetal Valproate Syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by a distinctive facial appearance, a cluster of minor and major anomalies, and central nervous system dysfunction. This syndrome is also exactly known as Fetal Valproic Acid Syndrome, Foetal Valproate Syndrome, and Foetal Valproic Acid Syndrome.

Kindler syndrome is a type of skin disease that is characterized by congenital blistering, skin atrophy, photosensitivity, skin fragility, and scaling. It has exact synonyms, including hereditary acrokeratotic poikiloderma of Kindler-Weary and poikiloderma of Kindler.

Kabuki syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by multiple congenital anomalies and mental retardation. It features a peculiar facial gestalt, short stature, skeletal and visceral abnormalities, cardiac anomalies, and immunological defects. Kabuki syndrome is also precisely known by other names, including KMS, Kabuki make-up syndrome, and Niikawa-Kuroki syndrome.

Familial erythrocytosis 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, primary polycythemia, and a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary polycythemia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VHL gene on chromosome 3p25. Furthermore, familial erythrocytosis 2 is also known by its exact synonyms: Chuvash erythromatosis, Chuvash polycythemia, Chuvash type polycythemia, ECYT2, and autosomal recessive benign erythrocytosis.

Myoclonic atonic epilepsy (MAE), also known precisely as EEOC and childhood onset epileptic encephalopathy, is categorized as a type of autosomal dominant disease and idiopathic generalized epilepsy. This condition is characterized by the presence of a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and typically begins during childhood. MAE is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy marked by the onset of multiple seizure types in the initial years of life, leading to a poor prognosis. Individuals affected by MAE experience cognitive regression and intellectual disability, which are attributed to a heterozygous mutation in the SLC6A1 gene located on chromosome 3p25.

Perlman syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by polyhydramnios with neonatal macrosomia, nephromegaly, distinctive facial appearance, renal dysplasia, nephroblastomatosis, and predisposition to Wilms tumor. This syndrome shows similarities to Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome. It has exact synonyms including nephroblastomatosis - fetal ascites - macrosomia - Wilms tumor, nephroblastomatosis, fetal ascites, macrosomia and Wilms tumor, and renal hamartomas, nephroblastomatosis and fetal gigantism.

Zika fever, also known as Zika virus disease, is a type of viral infectious disease characterized by several symptoms, including fever, rash, headaches, and joint pain. It is caused by the Zika virus, which targets neural progenitor cells and neuronal cells at all maturity stages. This disease is primarily transmitted by mosquitoes of the Aedes genus, specifically Aedes aegypti mosquitoes.

Shwachman Diamond Syndrome is a type of syndrome defined as a syndrome characterized by exocrine pancreatic insufficiency, bone marrow failure, and skeletal abnormalities. It has exact synonyms including Shwachman Syndrome, Shwachman-Bodian-Diamond Syndrome, Shwachman-Diamond type metaphyseal dysplasia, and pancreatic insufficiency and bone marrow dysfunction.
