Left ventricular noncompaction is a type of intrinsic cardiomyopathy and is characterized by a distinctive (spongy) morphological appearance of the LV myocardium. It is also exactly synonymous with left ventricular hypertrabeculation.

Goldberg-Shprintzen syndrome is a type of syndrome and autosomal recessive disease, which specifically exists due to some material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by intellectual disability, specific facial gestalt, and Hirschsprung's disease, resulting from a homozygous mutation in the KIAA1279 gene located on chromosome 10q21.1. Additionally, Goldberg-Shprintzen syndrome is exactly synonymous with Goldberg-Shprintzen megacolon syndrome.

Oculoauricular syndrome is a type of syndrome that is defined as a syndrome characterized by microcornea, microphthalmia, anterior-segment dysgenesis, cataract, coloboma of various parts of the eye, abnormalities of the retinal pigment epithelium, and rod-cone dystrophy, along with a particular cleft ear lobule.

Mednik syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by mental retardation, enteropathy, deafness, peripheral neuropathy, ichthyosis, and keratoderma. This syndrome is caused by a homozygous mutation in the AP1S1 gene on chromosome 7q22. It has exact synonyms including erythrokeratodermia variabilis 3, erythrokeratodermia variabilis, Kamouraska type, and mental retardation, enteropathy, deafness, neuropathy, ichthyosis, keratodermia.

East syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by seizures, sensorineural deafness, ataxia, mental retardation, and electrolyte imbalance, with its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KCNJ10 gene on chromosome 1q23. East syndrome has exact synonyms, including SeSAME syndrome, epilepsy, ataxia, sensorineural deafness and tubulopathy, and seizures, sensorineural deafness, ataxia, mental retardation and electrolyte imbalance.

Mowat Wilson Syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease that is fundamentally based on autosomal dominant inheritance. It is precisely defined as a syndrome characterized by distinctive facial features, intellectual disability, delayed development, and Hirschsprung disease, stemming from a de novo heterozygous mutation in the ZEB2 gene on chromosome 2q22. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with Hirschsprung disease mental retardation syndrome and also known as microcephaly, mental retardation, and distinct facial features, with or without Hirschsprung disease.

Perry syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by parkinsonism, hypoventilation, depression, and weight loss, and it has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DCTN1 gene on chromosome 2p13. Moreover, Perry syndrome has an exact synonym, which is parkinsonism with alveolar hypoventilation and mental depression.

Pitt Hopkins syndrome is an autosomal dominant disease and a type of syndrome that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by intellectual disability and developmental delay, breathing problems, recurrent seizures, and distinctive facial features, with its material basis lying in heterozygous de novo mutations in the TCF4 gene on chromosome 18q21.

Schimke immuno-osseous dysplasia is a type of autosomal recessive disease, spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia characterized by short stature with hyperpigmented macules, unusual facies, proteinuria with progressive renal failure, lymphopenia with recurrent infections, and cerebral ischemia. The disease has its material basis in mutations in the SMARCAL1 gene. Schimke immuno-osseous dysplasia is also known by its exact synonyms: Schimke immunoosseous dysplasia, Schimke syndrome, immunoosseous dysplasia Schimke type, and spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia - nephrotic syndrome.

Spoan syndrome is a neurodegenerative disease characterized by spastic paraplegia, axonal neuropathy, dysarthria, acoustic startle, and congenital optical atrophy, which falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is specifically caused by a homozygous mutation in the KLC2 gene on chromosome 11q13.2. Furthermore, Spoan syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: spastic paraplegia, optic atrophy, and neuropathy, as well as spastic paraplegia, optic atrophy, and neuropathy syndrome.

Chicken egg allergy is a type of egg allergy and is specifically an allergy triggered by Gallus gallus eggs, which are hen egg food products. It is also known by its exact synonym, Gallus gallus egg allergy.

Shellfish allergy is a type of food allergy that at least has an allergic trigger in some shellfish food products, including both mollusca and crustacea. It is defined as a food allergy triggered by Crustacea or Mollusca.

Respiratory allergy, which is the same as something that intersects allergic disease and at least one disease located in the respiratory tract, is a type of allergic disease. It is defined as an allergic disease that is located in the respiratory tract. Furthermore, respiratory allergy has an exact synonym: airway allergy.
Pollen allergy is a type of respiratory allergy defined as a respiratory allergy triggered by pollen.
Timothy grass allergy, a type of pollen allergy, is defined as a pollen allergy triggered by Phleum pratense pollen.
Autoimmune neuropathy, a type of autoimmune disease of the central nervous system, is defined as an autoimmune disease of the central nervous system caused by an autoimmune response.

A drug allergy is the same as an entity that represents the intersection of an allergic disease and an entity that has at least one allergic trigger, which is further defined as the intersection of a chemical entity and an entity that has at least one role as a drug. Furthermore, a drug allergy is a type of allergic disease. Additionally, a drug allergy is defined as an allergic disease that is triggered by a drug.

Metal allergy is an allergic disease that is triggered by a metal, which is defined as an allergic disease caused by something that falls within the intersection of diseases and entities that, at the least, have an allergic trigger from things that are either metal cations, metal atoms, or alkali metal salts. Essentially, metal allergy is a specific type of allergic disease characterized by its unique triggers and definition.
Gastrointestinal allergy is a type of allergic disease with a definition stating that it is an allergic disease located in the gastrointestinal tract.

Fruit allergy is a type of food allergy and also a type of condition that at least has an allergic trigger, specifically some plant fruit food product. It is defined as a food allergy triggered by a plant fruit product.

Apple allergy is a type of fruit allergy and it is also a type of condition that involves an allergic trigger to some apple food products. This condition is defined as a fruit allergy triggered by the Malus domestica plant's fruit food product. Additionally, apple allergy has an exact synonym, which is Malus domestica fruit allergy.

An apricot allergy is a type of fruit allergy that is specifically triggered by food products containing apricots, which come from the Prunus armeniaca plant. This condition is also exactly known as Prunus armeniaca fruit allergy.

Cherry allergy is a type of fruit allergy and is also a type of condition that is triggered by at least some cherry food products. It is defined as a fruit allergy triggered by the fruit of the Prunus avium plant. Additionally, cherry allergy has an exact synonym: Prunus avium fruit allergy.

Indian plum allergy is a type of fruit allergy that is specifically triggered by the Ziziphus mauritiana plant fruit food product. This condition is also exactly known as Ziziphus mauritiana fruit allergy.

Orange allergy is a type of fruit allergy and a specific kind of allergy that involves at least some food products made from oranges. It is defined as a fruit allergy triggered by the Citrus sinensis plant's fruit. Additionally, orange allergy is exactly synonymous with Citrus sinensis fruit allergy.

Melon allergy is a type of fruit allergy and is also a type of condition that is triggered by allergic reactions to some melon food products. This allergy is defined as a fruit allergy that is triggered by the fruit of the Cucumis melo plant. Additionally, melon allergy has an exact synonym: Cucumis melo fruit allergy.

Peach allergy is a type of fruit allergy and is also known as Prunus persica fruit allergy. It is defined as a fruit allergy triggered by food products from the Prunus persica plant. This type of allergy falls under the category of allergies caused by food products that contain peach as an allergic trigger.

Plum allergy is a type of fruit allergy that is triggered by the Prunus domestica plant fruit food product. This condition is also a type of allergy that results from consuming some plum fruit food products. Moreover, plum allergy is exactly synonymous with Prunus domestica fruit allergy.

Tomato allergy is a type of fruit allergy and it is also a type of condition that has an allergic trigger from some tomato food product. It is defined as a fruit allergy triggered by the Solanum lycopersicum plant fruit food product. Additionally, tomato allergy has an exact synonym: Solanum lycopersicum fruit allergy.
Fish allergy is a type of food allergy and is defined as a food allergy triggered by fish. It is a condition that involves an allergic trigger to some fish food products and to some actinopterygii.

Atlantic cod allergy, which is a type of fish allergy, is defined as a fish allergy triggered by Gadus morhua. This allergy is a type of condition that at least has an allergic trigger, specifically Gadus morhua. It also has the exact synonym "Gadus morhua fish allergy."

Atlantic salmon allergy is a type of fish allergy and is also known as Salmo salar fish allergy. It is triggered by Salmo salar and encompasses allergic reactions to some Atlantic salmon and trout food products. This allergy is defined as a fish allergy that is specifically caused by Salmo salar.

Carp allergy is a type of fish allergy and also a type of condition that gets triggered by at least some carp food products. It is defined as a fish allergy triggered by Cyprinus carpio. Additionally, carp allergy has an exact synonym: Cyprinus carpio fish allergy.

Zebrafish allergy is a type of fish allergy and is also known as Danio rerio allergy. It is defined as a fish allergy triggered by Danio rerio, indicating that it is a specific type of allergy with at least one allergic trigger being Danio rerio.

Rainbow trout allergy is a type of fish allergy that is specifically triggered by Oncorhynchus mykiss, which is another name for a rainbow trout. This allergy can be triggered by consuming rainbow trout food products. Additionally, it is defined as a fish allergy caused by Oncorhynchus mykiss and is also exactly synonymous with Oncorhynchus mykiss allergy.

Beta lactam allergy is a type of drug allergy and a type of condition that at least has an allergic trigger, which is some beta lactam. It is defined as a drug allergy that is triggered by a beta-lactam.

Penicillin allergy is a type of beta-lactam allergy and is also defined as a type of allergy that has an allergic trigger to some penicillin. Furthermore, it is defined as a beta-lactam allergy triggered by penicillin.
Cow milk allergy is a type of milk allergy and is defined as a milk allergy triggered by Bos taurus milk. It also has the exact synonym, "Bos taurus milk allergy."
Goat milk allergy is a type of milk allergy that is defined as an allergy triggered by Capra hircus milk. It is also exactly synonymous with Capra hircus milk allergy.

Mollusc allergy is a type of shellfish allergy and is defined as a shellfish allergy triggered by Mollusca. This allergy is a specific type of condition in which at least some mollusc food products serve as allergic triggers.

Crustacean allergy is a type of shellfish allergy and it is defined as a shellfish allergy triggered by Crustacea. It is a condition that at least involves some crustacean food product as an allergic trigger.

Brown shrimp allergy is a type of shrimp allergy and is also known as a Farfantepenaeus aztecus allergy. It is defined as a crustacean allergy triggered by Farfantepenaeus aztecus, indicating that it involves an allergic reaction to at least some part of Penaeus aztecus.

Crab allergy, a specific type of crustacean allergy, is defined as an allergic reaction triggered by Scylla paramamosain, also known as the green mud crab. This condition is precisely synonymous with both Scylla paramamosain allergy and green mud crab allergy.

Indian prawn allergy is a type of shrimp allergy and a type of something that at least has an allergic trigger, specifically Penaeus indicus. It is defined as a crustacean allergy triggered by Fenneropenaeus indicus. Additionally, Indian prawn allergy is exactly synonymous with Fenneropenaeus indicus allergy.

Tiger prawn allergy is a type of shrimp allergy and is also known as Penaeus monodon allergy. It is defined as a crustacean allergy triggered by Penaeus monodon, which means it is a condition that involves an allergic reaction to something that, at the very least, contains Penaeus monodon.

White shrimp allergy is a type of shrimp allergy and is also referred to as Litopenaeus vannamei allergy. It is defined as a crustacean allergy triggered by Litopenaeus vannamei, indicating that it is a condition that, at the very least, has an allergic trigger sourced from Penaeus vannamei.
Snail allergy is a type of mollusc allergy and is also a type of allergy that is triggered by some snail food product. It is defined as a mollusc allergy triggered by snails.

Horned turban snail allergy is a type of snail allergy that is triggered specifically by the horned turban snail, known scientifically as Turbo cornutus. This allergy is defined as a snail allergy caused by the horned turban snail. Moreover, it is exactly synonymous with Turbo cornutus allergy.

Latex allergy is a type of allergic disease and something that, at a minimum, has an allergic trigger from Hevea brasiliensis. Moreover, latex allergy is defined as an allergic disease that is triggered by latex.

Hepatoid adenocarcinoma is a type of adenocarcinoma, defined as an adenocarcinoma with morphologic characteristics similar to hepatocellular carcinoma, arising from an anatomic site other than the liver.

Warsaw Breakage Syndrome (WABS) is a type of syndrome that is an autosomal recessive disease, which means it has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically characterized by severe congenital microcephaly, growth restriction, and sensorineural hearing loss due to cochlear hypoplasia, with this set of symptoms having its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DDX11 gene on chromosome 12p11.

Mitochondrial Complex I deficiency, a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease, is characterized by a wide range of manifestations including marked and often fatal lactic acidosis, cardiomyopathy, leukoencephalopathy, pure myopathy, and hepatopathy with tubulopathy. This condition can present as various clinical phenotypes like Leigh syndrome, Leber hereditary optic neuropathy, and MELAS syndrome, with its material basis lying in mutations in multiple different genes, both nuclear-encoded and mitochondrial-encoded. It is also known by exact synonyms such as isolated NADH-CoQ reductase deficiency, isolated NADH-coenzyme Q reductase deficiency, isolated NADH-ubiquinone reductase deficiency, and isolated mitochondrial respiratory chain complex I deficiency.

Mitochondrial Complex II deficiency is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease, which also falls under a category of diseases that have a basis in some structural variant. This condition is defined as a mitochondrial metabolism disease characterized by a highly variable phenotype. Some patients experience multisystem involvement affecting the brain, heart, muscle, liver, and kidneys, which can result in death in infancy. Conversely, others may have only isolated cardiac or muscle involvement with onset in adulthood and maintain normal cognition. The condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the nuclear-encoded SDHA gene on chromosome 5p, the nuclear-encoded SDHAF1 gene on chromosome 19q, or the nuclear-encoded SDHD gene on chromosome 11q23. Mitochondrial Complex II deficiency is precisely synonymous with isolated mitochondrial respiratory chain complex II deficiency, isolated succinate-CoQ reductase deficiency, isolated succinate-coenzyme Q reductase deficiency, and isolated succinate-ubiquinone reductase deficiency.

Purpura fulminans is a type of purpura and something that at least has the symptom of some necrosis. It is defined as a purpura characterized by blood spots, bruising, and discoloration of the skin resulting from coagulation in small blood vessels within the skin, which rapidly leads to skin necrosis and disseminated intravascular coagulation. This condition is often fatal. Additionally, purpura fulminans is exactly synonymous with purpura gangrenosa.

Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome 1 is a type of Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome. This syndrome is defined as a Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome that has its material basis in either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the HPS1 gene located on chromosome 10q24.

Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome 2 is a type of Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome. It is defined as a Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the beta-3A subunit of the AP3 complex (AP3B1) on chromosome 5q14.1.

Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome 3 is a type of Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome, defined by a Hermasky-Pudlak syndrome that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the HPS3 gene on chromosome 3q24.

Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome 4 is a subtype of Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome. It is defined as a Hermansky-Pudlak Syndrome that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HPS4 gene located on chromosome 22q12.1.

Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome 5 is a type of Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome and is defined as a Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the HPS5 gene on chromosome 11p14.

Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome 6 is a type of Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome, defined as a Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the HPS6 gene on chromosome 10q24.

Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome 7 is a type of Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome and is defined by a Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the DTNBP1 gene located on chromosome 6p22.3.

Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome 8 is a type of Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome and it is defined as a Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the BLOC1S3 gene on chromosome 19q13.

Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome 9 is a type of Hermansky Pudlak Syndrome. It is defined as a Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome that has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the gene encoding palladin (BLOC1S6) on chromosome 15q21.

Luminal breast carcinoma A is a type of breast carcinoma characterized by high expression of genes characteristic of luminal epithelial cells, including estrogen receptor (ER), estrogen-regulated protein LIV-1, and the transcription factors hepatocyte nuclear factor 3 (HNF3A), XBP1, and GATA 3. It is broadly synonymous with breast tumor luminal and luminal breast cancer, and it has an exact synonym, Luminal A Breast Carcinoma.

Barber Say syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by the association of excessive hair growth (hypertrichosis), papery thin and fragile (atrophic) skin, outward turned eyelids (ectropion), and a large mouth (macrostomia). It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TWIST2 gene on chromosome 2q37.

Ablepharon Macrostomia Syndrome is a syndrome that is a type of autosomal dominant disease, and it involves a material basis in an autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by features including ablepharon, macrostomia, abnormal external ears, syndactyly of the hands and feet, dry and coarse skin or redundant folds of skin, absent or sparse hair, genital malformations, and developmental delay. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TWIST2 gene located on chromosome 2q37.

Poikiloderma with neutropenia is a type of autosomal recessive disease, skin disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a skin disease characterized by poikiloderma, hyperkeratotic nails, generalized hyperkeratosis on palms and soles, neutropenia, short stature, and recurrent pulmonary infections. The condition has its material basis in a mutation in the C16ORF57 gene on chromosome 16q13. It also has the exact synonym poikiloderma with neutropenia, Clericuzio type.

Kufor Rakeb syndrome is a form of early-onset Parkinson's disease, which is also known as autosomal recessive Parkinson disease 9 and autosomal recessive juvenile onset Parkinson disease 9. This condition is characterized by an autosomal recessive disease type and has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, Kufor Rakeb syndrome is defined by early-onset Parkinson's disease features such as supranuclear gaze palsy, spasticity, and dementia. This is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in a lysosomal type 5 ATPase encoding gene located on chromosome 1p36.

Ataxia with oculomotor apraxia type 3, which has the exact synonym ataxia-oculomotor apraxia 3, is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by worsening poor coordination and balance (ataxia) over time. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PIK3R5 gene located on chromosome 17p13.

Lethal congenital contracture syndrome is a type of syndrome classified as an autosomal recessive disease and a physical disorder. It is rooted in autosomal recessive inheritance and stems from abnormalities in prenatal development or birth, affecting the skeletal joints. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by congenital nonprogressive joint contractures, which can involve the upper or lower limbs and/or the vertebral column, leading to various degrees of flexion or extension limitations evident at birth.

Lethal congenital contracture syndrome 1 (LCCS1), which is also known as multiple contracture syndrome, Finnish type, is a type of lethal congenital contracture syndrome. This syndrome falls under a category of diseases that have their basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, LCCS1 is defined by a lethal congenital contracture syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the mRNA export mediator, the GLE1 gene, located on chromosome 9q34.

Lethal congenital contracture syndrome 2 (LCCS2), also known exactly as multiple contracture syndrome, Israeli-Bedouin type, is a specific type of lethal congenital contracture syndrome. This syndrome is characterized by abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The definition of LCCS2 indicates that it is a lethal congenital contracture syndrome with a material basis in homozygous mutation in the ERBB3 gene on chromosome 12q13.

Anomalous left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery is a type of coronary artery anomaly characterized by the branching off of the left coronary artery (LCA) from the pulmonary artery instead of the aortic sinus. This condition is precisely referred to as ALCAPA, Bland-White-Garland syndrome, or White-Garland syndrome, which are its exact synonyms.
Char syndrome is a type of patent ductus arteriosus that is defined as a patent ductus arteriosus with facial dysmorphism and abnormal fifth digits.

Spinal disease is the same as something that is an intersection of a disease and something that, at a minimum, has a location in the vertebral column. Additionally, spinal disease is a type of bone disease and has the definition of being a bone disease that is located in the spine.

Ritscher-Schinzel syndrome is a monogenic disease and a type of syndrome that is based on a genetic foundation. It is characterized by a combination of craniofacial, cerebellar, and cardiac anomalies including a prominent occiput and forehead, hypertelorism, ocular coloboma, cleft palate, Dandy-Walker malformation, cerebellar vermis hypoplasia, tetralogy of Fallot, atrial, and ventricular septal defects. Additionally, Ritscher-Schinzel syndrome is exactly synonymous with CCC dysplasia and craniocerebellocardiac dysplasia.

Holzgreve Wagner Rehder syndrome is a type of syndrome defined by a set of characteristics including Potter sequence, heart defect, cleft palate, polydactyly, and skeletal defects. It is also exactly synonymous with Holzgreve Wagner Rehder Syndrome and Holzgreve syndrome.

Erythema elevatum diutinum is a type of vasculitis characterized by red, purple, brown, or yellow papules (raised spots), plaques, or nodules. These are found on the backs of the hands, other extensor surfaces overlying joints, and on the buttocks.

Hypertrichotic osteochondrodysplasia Cantu type is a type of osteochondrodysplasia that is characterized by congenital hypertrichosis, neonatal macrosomia, and cardiomegaly. It also has the exact synonym Cantu syndrome.

Cardiac tuberculosis is the same as an intersection of something that is tuberculosis and something that is a disease located in the heart. It is a type of heart disease and also a type of tuberculosis. Cardiac tuberculosis is defined as tuberculosis located in the heart. Furthermore, it has a narrow synonym: cardiovascular tuberculosis.

Ritscher-Schinzel Syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of Ritscher-Schinzel Syndrome, characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined by a Ritscher-Schinzel syndrome that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the KIAA0196 gene on chromosome 8q24.

Ritscher-Schinzel Syndrome 2 is a type of Ritscher-Schinzel Syndrome and a type of X-linked recessive disease, which means it is something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a Ritscher-Schinzel syndrome that has a material basis in mutation in the CCDC22 gene on chromosome Xp11.

Von Willebrand's Disease 1 is a type of Von Willebrand's Disease characterized by a quantitative partial deficiency of circulating VWF, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the VWF gene on chromosome 12p13. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms such as VWD type 1, VWD1, von Willebrand disease type 1, and von Willebrand disease type I.

Von Willebrand's disease 2 is a type of Von Willebrand's disease, characterized by qualitative but not quantitative abnormalities of the VWF protein. This condition has a material basis in a mutation in the VWF gene, which is located on chromosome 12p13. It is precisely referred to by several synonyms, including VWD type 2, VWD2, von Willebrand disease type 2, and von Willebrand disease type II.

3MC syndrome 1 is a type of 3MC syndrome characterized by a specific definition. It is a 3MC syndrome that has its material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of a homozygous mutation in the mannan binding lectin serine peptidase 1 gene (MASP1) located on chromosome 3q27.

3MC syndrome 2 is a type of 3MC syndrome and is disjoint with 3MC syndrome 3. It is defined as a 3MC syndrome that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous mutation in the collectin subfamily member 11 gene (COLEC11) on chromosome 2p25.
3MC syndrome 3 is a type of 3MC syndrome characterized by a 3MC syndrome that has its material basis in a compound heterozygous mutation in the COLEC10 gene located on chromosome 8q24.

Noonan Syndrome 1 is a type of Noonan Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which specifically has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Noonan Syndrome that has its material basis in the PTPN11 gene on chromosome 12q24. Moreover, Noonan Syndrome 1 is exactly synonymous with NS1.

Noonan Syndrome 2 (NS2) is a type of Noonan Syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy and has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. NS2 is also known by its exact synonym, NS2.

Noonan syndrome 3 is a type of Noonan syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Noonan syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KRAS gene. Furthermore, Noonan syndrome 3 is exactly synonymous with NS3.

Noonan syndrome 4 (NS4) is a type of Noonan syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease that primarily has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined by a Noonan syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SOS1 gene located on chromosome 2p22.

Noonan Syndrome 5, which is also known by its exact synonym NS5, is categorized as a type of Noonan Syndrome and falls under the broader classification of autosomal dominant diseases. It is specifically characterized as a type of condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Additionally, Noonan Syndrome 5 is defined by its material basis, which is a mutation in the RAF1 gene.

Noonan syndrome 6 is a type of Noonan syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Noonan syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NRAS gene on chromosome 1p13. Additionally, Noonan syndrome 6 is exactly synonymous with NS6.

Noonan syndrome 7 is a type of Noonan syndrome, which is an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome has a definition as a Noonan syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BRAF gene. Additionally, Noonan syndrome 7 has an exact synonym, NS7.

Noonan syndrome 8 is a type of Noonan syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease that fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This specific syndrome is defined by a Noonan syndrome that has its material basis caused by a heterozygous mutation in the RIT1 gene located on chromosome 1q22. Additionally, Noonan syndrome 8 is exactly synonymous with NS8.

Noonan Syndrome 9 is a type of Noonan Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This specific syndrome is defined by having a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SOS2 gene located on chromosome 14q21. Additionally, Noonan Syndrome 9 is exactly synonymous with NS9.

Noonan Syndrome 10 is a type of Noonan Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Noonan Syndrome that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the LZTR1 gene on chromosome 22q11. Additionally, Noonan Syndrome 10 is exactly synonymous with NS10.

Yunis Varon syndrome is a syndrome that is autosomal recessive, which means it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by skeletal defects, including cleidocranial dysplasia and digital anomalies, as well as severe neurologic involvement with neuronal loss. This syndrome also features enlarged cytoplasmic vacuoles in neurons, muscle, and cartilage, and is usually lethal in infancy. The condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FIG4 gene on chromosome 6q21. Yunis Varon syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: cleidocranial dysplasia with micrognathia, absent thumbs, and distal aphalangia, and cleidocranial dysplasia-micrognathia-absent thumbs syndrome.

XFE progeroid syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of progeroid syndrome, which inherently has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is defined by its characteristic features, including an aged bird-like facies, lack of subcutaneous fat, dwarfism, cachexia, and microcephaly, all of which are attributable to a homozygous mutation in the ERCC4 gene located on chromosome 16p13. Additionally, XFE progeroid syndrome is exactly synonymous with XFEPS and XPF-ERCC1 progeroid syndrome.

Whim syndrome is a type of disease that falls under three categories: it is an autosomal dominant disease, a primary immunodeficiency disease, and it is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an immunodeficiency disease marked by neutropenia, hypogammaglobulinemia, and extensive human papillomavirus infection, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the CXCR4 gene located on chromosome 2q22. Moreover, Whim syndrome has three exact synonyms: WHIMS, warts, hypogammaglobulinemia, infections, and myelokathexis, and warts-hypogammaglobulinemia-infections-myelokathexis syndrome.

B cell adult acute lymphocytic leukemia is a type of lymphoma and also a type of adult acute lymphocytic leukemia. It is characterized as a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some lymphocyte of B lineage and its existence starts during adult onset. This condition is defined as an adult acute lymphoblastic leukemia occurring in adults that has a material basis in B lymphocytes. It is exactly synonymous with several terms including B-cell adult acute lymphocytic leukaemia, adult B acute lymphoblastic leukaemia, adult B acute lymphoblastic leukemia, adult B-lymphoblastic leukaemia, adult B-lymphoblastic leukemia, adult b-cell acute lymphoblastic leukaemia, adult b-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia, adult b-cell lymphocytic leukaemia, and adult b-cell lymphocytic leukemia.

Atypical chronic myeloid leukemia BCR-ABL1 negative is a type of myelodysplastic myeloproliferative neoplasm characterized by the principal involvement of the neutrophil series with leukocytosis and multilineage dysplasia. Notably, the neoplastic cells do not have a Philadelphia chromosome or the BCR/ABL fusion gene. This condition is exactly synonymous with aCML, atypical CML, atypical chronic myeloid leukaemia, atypical chronic myeloid leukaemia BCR-ABL1 negative, atypical chronic myeloid leukemia BCR-ABL1 negative, and subacute myeloid leukemia.

Nance Horan Syndrome is a type of syndrome and a specific form of X-linked dominant disease, which is based on some form of X-linked dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome that stems from a mutation in the NHS gene located on chromosome Xp22, characterized by congenital cataract leading to profound vision loss, distinctive dysmorphic features, and dental anomalies.

Alpha 2 plasmin inhibitor deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive and hemorrhagic disease, which also falls under categories of conditions that at least have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and those that have symptoms including bleeding. This condition is defined as a hemorrhagic disease that has its material basis in mutation in the PLI gene, characterized by a hemorrhagic tendency evident from childhood, which includes prolonged bleeding and ecchymoses following minor trauma, as well as spontaneous bleeding episodes. Furthermore, alpha 2 plasmin inhibitor deficiency is exactly synonymous with antiplasmin deficiency and plasmin inhibitor deficiency.

Alpha methylacyl CoA racemase deficiency is classified as a type of peroxisomal disease and is also precisely identified as AMACR deficiency. It is defined as a peroxisomal disease characterized by retinitis pigmentosa leading to progressive visual failure, learning difficulties, peripheral neuropathy, and hypogonadism. This condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the AMACR gene located on chromosome 5p13.2-q11.1.

Isolated anhidrosis with normal sweat glands is a type of anhidrosis, which is defined as an anhidrosis that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the ITPR2 gene on chromosome 12p11. Additionally, this condition is exactly synonymous with Dann-Epstein-Sohar syndrome.

Ankyloglossia is a type of tongue disease that is characterized by an unusually short, thick lingual frenulum, a membrane connecting the underside of the tongue to the floor of the mouth. It has an exact synonym, tongue-tie, and an exact match with MESH:D000072676.

Fetal nicotine spectrum disorder is a type of specific developmental disorder, characterized by physical, behavioral, and learning birth defects resulting from maternal ingestion of nicotine during pregnancy.

Microcephalic osteodysplastic primordial dwarfism type I is a condition that is classified in several ways: it is a type of autosomal recessive disease, osteochondrodysplasia, and it is also defined by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is precisely characterized by dwarfism, microcephaly, mental retardation, brain malformations, and ocular and auditory sensory deficits. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RNU4ATAC gene, which encodes a small nuclear RNA component of the U12-dependent spliceosome, located on chromosome 2q14.2. Furthermore, microcephalic osteodysplastic primordial dwarfism type I is known by several exact synonyms, including Taybi-Linder syndrome, brachymelic primordial dwarfism, cephaloskeletal dysplasia, low-birth-weight dwarfism with skeletal dysplasia, and osteodysplastic primordial dwarfism type I.

Microcephalic osteodysplastic primordial dwarfism type II (MOPD II) is a condition that falls under several categories: it is a type of autosomal recessive disease, osteochondrodysplasia, and is defined by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, MOPD II is characterized by a microcephalic osteodysplastic primordial dwarfism that originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PCNT gene, which encodes pericentrin, located on chromosome 21q22. This condition is distinguished by intrauterine growth retardation, severe proportionate short stature, and microcephaly. Additionally, MOPD II is also known by its exact synonyms: Majewski osteodysplastic primordial dwarfism type II and osteodysplastic primordial dwarfism type II.

Megacystis microcolon intestinal hypoperistalsis syndrome is a type of syndrome that is defined by marked dilatation of the bladder and microcolon and decreased intestinal peristalsis. It has exact synonyms which include Berdon syndrome, Megacystis microcolon intestinal hypoperistalsis syndrome, megacystis-microcolon-intestinal hypoperistalsis syndrome (MMIH), and visceral myopathy.

Abdominal obesity metabolic syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by abdominal obesity, blood lipid disorders, inflammation, insulin resistance or full-blown diabetes, and an increased risk of developing cardiovascular disease.

Abdominal obesity metabolic syndrome 3 is a type of abdominal obesity metabolic syndrome, defined as an abdominal obesity-metabolic syndrome that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the DYRK1B gene on chromosome 19q13.

X-linked cleft palate with or without ankyloglossia is a type of X-linked monogenic disease, and it is also a type of cleft palate. This condition is characterized as something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a cleft palate that has a material basis in mutation in the TBX22 gene on chromosome Xq21. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: X-linked cleft palate and ankyloglossia.

Ulnar mammary syndrome, which is also known exactly as Pallister ulnar-mammary syndrome and Schinzel syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a syndrome. It is characterized by a range of symptoms including posterior limb deficiencies or duplications, apocrine/mammary gland hypoplasia and/or dysfunction, abnormal dentition, delayed puberty in males, and genital anomalies. This syndrome has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TBX3 gene and is a condition that inherently involves some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Neonatal diabetes mellitus with congenital hypothyroidism, also known as NDH syndrome, is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, physical disorder, and neonatal diabetes. It is characterized by a condition that necessarily has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is grounded in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, neonatal diabetes mellitus with congenital hypothyroidism is defined as a neonatal diabetes distinguished by intrauterine growth retardation, hypothyroidism, and the onset of nonimmune diabetes mellitus within the first few weeks of life. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GLIS3 gene on chromosome 9p24.

Permanent neonatal diabetes mellitus (PNDM) is a type of neonatal diabetes, which is characterized by various genetic bases. It can be considered an autosomal dominant disease and also an autosomal recessive disease. The material basis of PNDM can be found in specific genetic inheritances; it is associated with autosomal dominant inheritance and with autosomal recessive inheritance as well. The condition is defined as a neonatal diabetes that results from a homozygous mutation in the glucokinase gene (GCK), heterozygous mutations in the KCNJ11 and INS genes, or by either heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the ABCC8 gene. Additionally, PNDM is known by exact synonyms including PDMI, permanent diabetes mellitus of infancy, and its abbreviation PNDM itself.

Ethylmalonic encephalopathy is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease, which is characterized by neurodevelopmental delay and regression, prominent pyramidal and extrapyramidal signs, recurrent petechiae, orthostatic acrocyanosis, and chronic diarrhea. This condition is associated with symptoms such as neurodevelopmental delay and diarrhea, and its disease basis involves some structural variant. Furthermore, ethylmalonic encephalopathy has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ETHE1 gene, which encodes a mitochondrial matrix protein, located on chromosome 19q13.

Endocrine cerebro osteodysplasia syndrome, also exactly known as ECO syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is a syndrome defined by multiple congenital defects in endocrine, cerebral, and skeletal systems, which lead to neonatal mortality, and it has its material basis in a mutation in the gene encoding intestinal cell kinase.

Recessive dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa (RDEB) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is also known as epidermolysis bullosa dystrophica. It falls under the category of diseases that inherently have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. RDEB is characterized by recurrent blistering at the level of the sublamina densa beneath the cutaneous basement membrane and is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene encoding type VII collagen (COL7A1) on chromosome 3p21. It is exactly synonymous with RDEB, Hallopeau-Siemens type, and autosomal recessive dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa generalisata gravis, including a specific mention of the autosomal recessive dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa, Hallopeau-Siemens type. Additionally, RDEB has narrow synonyms, including severe generalized RDEB and severe generalized recessive dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa, indicating more specific forms or severity within the broader condition.

Primary sclerosing cholangitis is a type of sclerosing cholangitis, defined as a sclerosing cholangitis characterized by fibroobliterative inflammation of the biliary tract, leading to cirrhosis and portal hypertension.

Chondrodysplasia pseudohermaphroditism syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by the clinical features of 46,XY complete gonadal dysgenesis in association with severe dwarfism with generalized chondrodysplasia. It is also known by the exact synonyms Nivelon-Nivelon-Mabille syndrome and chondrodysplasia-disorder of sex development syndrome.

Chronic recurrent multifocal osteomyelitis (CRMO), also known as chronic multifocal osteomyelitis, is a type of spinal disease and a form of osteomyelitis. This condition is characterized by multiple foci of painful swelling of bones, primarily located in the metaphyses of the long bones, as well as in the pelvis, the shoulder girdle, and the spine. It affects various locations including the vertebral column, the bony pelvis, and the limb long bones.

Congenital chylothorax is a type of physical disorder, pleural disease, and something that has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a pleural disease characterized by the accumulation of chyle within the pleural space, leading to respiratory distress, malnutrition, and immunological compromise, either immediately after birth or within the first few weeks of life.

Fetal encasement syndrome, also exactly known as cocoon syndrome, is a type of syndrome and a specific instance of an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. The syndrome is defined as having a material basis in homozygous mutation in the CHUK gene located on chromosome 10q24. It is characterized by multiple fetal malformations, including a defective face and seemingly absent limbs, which are bound to the trunk and encased under the skin.

Anterior segment dysgenesis is a type of monogenic and eye disease that also falls under the category of diseases with a basis in genetics. It is defined as an eye disease characterized by various symptoms including iris hypoplasia, altered corneal diameter, corneal vascularization and opacity, posterior embryotoxon, corectopia, polycoria, abnormal iridocorneal angle, ectopia lentis, and anterior synechiae between the iris and posterior corneal surface, specifically located in the anterior segment of the eye. Furthermore, it is known by exact synonyms such as anterior segment developmental anomaly, corneal opacification and other ocular anomalies, and sclerocornea with other ocular anomalies.

Congenital hereditary endothelial dystrophy of the cornea, also known exactly as CHED, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, corneal endothelial dystrophy, and physical disorder. It is characterized by conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and abnormalities related to prenatal development or birth. Specifically, this corneal endothelial dystrophy results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC4A11 gene, which encodes a sodium borate cotransporter, located on chromosome 20p13. The disease is characterized by thickening and opacification of the cornea, altered morphology of the endothelium, and secretion of an abnormal collagenous layer at the Descemet membrane.

Dicarboxylic aminoaciduria is a type of autosomal recessive disease and an amino acid metabolic disorder that is characterized by an excess urinary excretion of aspartate and glutamate acidic amino acids. It also has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, dicarboxylic aminoaciduria has the exact synonym "glutamate-aspartate transport defect."

MYH 9 related disease is a type of blood platelet disease. It is defined as a blood platelet disease that has its material basis in mutations in the MYH9 gene and is characterized by thrombocytopenia, enlarged platelets, sensorineural hearing loss, and presenile cataract.

Familial erythrocytosis 1 is an autosomal dominant disease that is a type of primary polycythemia. It is also identified as something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined as a primary polycythemia that has its material basis in a mutation in the gene encoding the erythropoietin receptor, characterized by increased serum red blood cell mass and hemoglobin concentration, hypersensitivity of erythroid progenitors to erythropoietin (EPO), and low serum levels of EPO. Familial erythrocytosis 1 is exactly synonymous with ECYT1, autosomal dominant benign erythrocytosis, and primary familial and congenital polycythemia.

Lethal congenital contracture syndrome 3 is a subtype of lethal congenital contracture syndrome, which is categorized as a disease that originates from abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. It is defined by a lethal congenital contracture syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous mutations in the PIP5K1C gene located on chromosome 19p13. Additionally, it is precisely synonymous with Israeli Bedouin type B multiple contracture syndrome and has an exact match with OMIM:611369.

Lethal congenital contracture syndrome 4 is a type of lethal congenital contracture syndrome and also falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a lethal congenital contracture syndrome that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the MYBPC1 gene on chromosome 12q23. Additionally, it has an exact match with OMIM:614915.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis (ARCI) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, physical disorder, and ichthyosis, which has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is linked to abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is characterized by abnormal skin scaling over the whole body due to a defect in keratinization. ARCI is also known by its exact synonyms: lamellar ichthyosis and non bullous congenital ichthyosiform erythroderma.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 1 (ARCI1), also known narrowly as bathing suit ichthyosis, is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis. It falls under the broader category of diseases that originate from abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. ARCI1 is specifically characterized by lamellar ichthyosis, ectropion, eclabium, and hyperkeratosis, which result from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TGM1 gene located on chromosome 14q11.2.

Anencephaly is a type of congenital nervous system abnormality, which is defined as a congenital nervous system abnormality characterized by the failure of the anterior neuropore to close, resulting in partial or complete absence of the cranial vault, accompanied by the absence of overlying tissues, including the brain and cerebral hemispheres, skull, and scalp. Additionally, anencephaly has an exact match with MESH:D000757.

Cerebral cavernous malformation is a type of cerebrovascular disease that is characterized by dilated blood-filled capillaries lacking structural support. It is a condition that occurs in the cerebrum. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms, including cavernous angiomatous malformations, cerebral capillary malformations, and familial cavernous angioma. Moreover, cerebral cavernous malformation has an exact match with OMIM entry PS116860.
Cerebral cavernous malformation 2 is a type of cerebral cavernous malformation, defined as a cerebral cavernous malformation that has a material basis in mutation in the CCM2 gene on chromosome 7p13.

Cerebral cavernous malformation 3 is a type of cerebral cavernous malformation, which is defined as a cerebral cavernous malformation that has a material basis in mutation in the PDCD10 gene on chromosome 3q26.1.

GRN-related frontotemporal lobar degeneration with TDP43 inclusions is a type of autosomal dominant disease, a type of frontotemporal dementia, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a frontotemporal dementia characterized by variable phenotypic expression typically including social, behavioral, or language deterioration, rather than memory or motor deficits, and the presence of TARDBP-positive inclusions. This condition has a material basis in mutation in the GRN gene on chromosome 17q21.31.

Peter's anomaly is a type of corneal disease characterized by a central corneal leukoma, absence of the posterior corneal stroma, and Descemet membrane. This condition has its material basis in mutations in several genes: the PAX6 gene on chromosome 11p13, the PITX2 gene on chromosome 4q25, the CYP1B1 gene on chromosome 2p22.2, or the FOXC1 gene on chromosome 6p25.3.

Catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia is a type of monogenic and heart conduction disease, which is characterized by a heart conduction disease that manifests as adrenergically induced ventricular tachycardia, leading to syncope and sudden death during exercise, stress, or catecholamine infusion without the presence of structural cardiac abnormalities. It is also described as a condition that at least has the symptom of some ventricular tachycardia and has a basis in some gene, underlining its genetic foundation.

Catecholaminergic Polymorphic Ventricular Tachycardia 1 (CPVT1) is a subtype of catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia, which inherently presents with symptoms including ventricular tachycardia. It is specifically characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance and has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RYR2 gene located on chromosome 1q43. Furthermore, CPVT1 is precisely synonymous with CVPT1 and also known as arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia 2.

Catecholaminergic Polymorphic Ventricular Tachycardia 2 (CPVT2) is a specific type of Catecholaminergic Polymorphic Ventricular Tachycardia, which inherently includes some form of ventricular tachycardia as a symptom. It is defined as a Catecholaminergic Polymorphic Ventricular Tachycardia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CASQ2 gene on chromosome 1p13. Additionally, CPVT2 is exactly synonymous with CVPT2.

Catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia 3 (CPVT3) is a type of catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia, which is a condition that inherently exhibits symptoms of ventricular tachycardia. It is defined as a catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia characterized by early onset mortality and has its material basis in variation in the chromosomal region 7p22-p14. Additionally, CPVT3 is exactly synonymous with CVPT3.

Catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia 4 (CPVT4) is a type of catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia and is characterized by at least having the symptom of some ventricular tachycardia. It is defined as a catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia that is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance and has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CALM1 gene on chromosome 14q32. Furthermore, CPVT4 has the exact synonym CVPT4.

Catecholaminergic Polymorphic Ventricular Tachycardia 5 (CPVT5) is a type of catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia and is also a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some ventricular tachycardia. It is defined as a catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TRDN gene on chromosome 6q22. Furthermore, CPVT5 has the exact synonym CVPT5.

Pigment dispersion syndrome is a type of eye disease. It is defined as an eye disease characterized by slit-like depigmented areas of the iris, with up to 50% of patients going on to develop glaucoma. Moreover, it has exact synonyms, which include glaucoma-related pigment dispersion syndrome and pigment-dispersion type glaucoma.

Autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of frontal lobe epilepsy, which is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a frontal lobe epilepsy that is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance with childhood onset of clusters of brief nocturnal motor seizures with hyperkinetic or tonic manifestations. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, ENFL.

Autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy, and it is defined as an autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CHRNA4 gene on chromosome 20q13. Additionally, autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 1 has exact synonyms including ENFL1 and nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 1.

Autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 2 is a type of autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 15q24. Additionally, autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 2 has exact synonyms ENFL2 and nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 2.

Autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 3 is a type of autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy and is defined as an autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CHRNB2 gene on chromosome 1q21. Moreover, autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 3 has exact synonyms, including ENFL3 and nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 3.

Autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 4 is a type of autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CHRNA2 gene on chromosome 8p21. Additionally, it has the exact synonyms ENFL4 and nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 4.

Autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 5 is a specific type of autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy that arises due to a heterozygous mutation in the KCNT1 gene located on chromosome 9q34. Additionally, this condition is precisely synonymous with ENFL5 and nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy 5.

Arteriovenous malformations of the brain are recognized as a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm, hemangioma, cerebrovascular disease, and something that notably derives from some endothelial cells. Additionally, they are categorized as a type of condition that has its location in the brain. The definition of arteriovenous malformations of the brain is a central nervous system benign neoplasm that derives from endothelial cells and is located in the brain. Furthermore, arteriovenous malformations of the brain are exactly synonymous with cerebral arteriovenous malformation and intracranial arteriovenous malformation.

Atrichia with papular lesions is a type of autosomal recessive disease, alopecia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an alopecia characterized by irreversible hair loss during the neonatal period on all hair-bearing areas of the body, followed by the development of papular lesions all over the body, which has a material basis in mutations in the HR gene on chromosome 8p21.3. Furthermore, atrichia with papular lesions has the exact synonym papular atrichia.

Autosomal dominant auditory neuropathy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness and has the definition of an autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness characterized by the preservation of outer hair cell function and abnormal or absent auditory brainstem responses, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DIAPH3 gene on chromosome 13q. Furthermore, autosomal dominant auditory neuropathy 1 has exact synonyms including AUNA1, NSDAN, and nonsyndromic dominant auditory neuropathy.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 16 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is also a type of blood platelet disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and presents symptoms such as bleeding. Specifically, it is a blood platelet disease characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance with macrothrombocytopenia, platelet anisocytosis, prolonged bleeding time, but only a mildly increased bleeding tendency. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ITGA2B gene on chromosome 17q21.31 or the ITGB3 gene on chromosome 17q21.32. Furthermore, Platelet type bleeding disorder 16 is also known by its exact synonyms, autosomal dominant Glanzmann thrombasthenia and autosomal dominant thrombasthenia of Glanzmann and Naegeli.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 8 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of blood platelet disease, which at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and has bleeding as a symptom. This disorder is characterized by mild to moderate mucocutaneous bleeding and an absence of adenosine phosphate-induced platelet aggregation, due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the P2RY12 gene on chromosome 3q. Additionally, Platelet type bleeding disorder 8 is also exactly synonymous with ADP platelet receptor P2Y12 defect and P2Y12 defect.

Brunner Syndrome is a type of X-linked recessive disease and an amino acid metabolic disorder, which is a condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by recessive X-linked inheritance, impaired monoamine metabolism, impulsive aggressiveness, and mild mental retardation, which has its material basis in a mutation in the MAOA gene on chromosome Xp11. Additionally, Brunner Syndrome has the exact synonym, monoamine oxidase A deficiency.

Cayman type cerebellar ataxia is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, also known exactly as Cayman cerebellar ataxia. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by marked autosomal recessive inheritance, psychomotor retardation, cerebellar dysfunction including nystagmus, intention tremor, dysarthria, and wide-based ataxic gait, hypotonia, and the absence of retinal abnormalities. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the ATCAY gene on chromosome 19p13.3.

Hyperekplexia is a type of nervous system disease characterized by an exaggerated startle response to sudden, unexpected auditory or tactile stimuli and hypertonia. It is also known by exact synonyms such as Kok disease, congenital stiff man syndrome, familial startle disease, hereditary hyperekplexia, and startle disease. Moreover, hyperekplexia has an exact match with GARD:3129.

Hyperekplexia 1 is a type of hyperekplexia and has the exact synonym HKPX1. It is described as a type of autosomal dominant disease and also as a type of autosomal recessive disease, indicating that it has a material basis in both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, hyperekplexia 1 is defined as a hyperekplexia that has its material basis in heterozygous, homozygous, or compound heterozygous mutation in the GLRA1 gene on chromosome 5q32.

Hyperekplexia 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific kind of hyperekplexia that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hyperekplexia that arises from compound heterozygous or homozygous mutation in the GLRB gene located on chromosome 4q32. Additionally, Hyperekplexia 2 is exactly synonymous with HKPX2.

Hyperekplexia 3, which has the exact synonym HKPX3, is a type of hyperekplexia. It is characterized as both an autosomal dominant and an autosomal recessive disease. Furthermore, it is defined as a hyperekplexia that possesses a material basis in either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC6A5 gene located on chromosome 11p15. This condition is also described as having a basis in some form of autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance.

Familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia (FHH) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, hypercalcemia, and inherited metabolic disorder. It is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance with elevated serum calcium levels and decreased urinary calcium excretion. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms, including FBH, FBHH, familial benign hypercalcemia, and familial benign hypocalciuric hypercalcemia. Furthermore, familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia 1 is a type of familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia that is defined by a familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia which has its material basis in heterozygous loss-of-function mutations in the CASR gene on chromosome 3q21. Moreover, familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia 1 is exactly synonymous with FHH type 1, HHC1, familial benign hypercalcemia 1, familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia type I, and hypocalciuric hypercalcemia type I.

Familial Hypocalciuric Hypercalcemia 2 (FHH2) is a type of Familial Hypocalciuric Hypercalcemia. It is defined by a familial condition that stems from a heterozygous mutation in the GNA11 gene located on chromosome 19p13. FHH2 is precisely known by several synonyms: FHH Type 2, HHC2, Familial Hypocalciuric Hypercalcemia Type 2, and Hypocalciuric Hypercalcemia Type II, highlighting its positional identity within the broader spectrum of Familial Hypocalciuric Hypercalcemia.

Familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia 3 is a type of familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia and has a definition as a familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the AP2S1 gene on chromosome 19q13. It has exact synonyms including FHH type 3, HHC3, familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia type 3, and hypocalciuric hypercalcemia type III.

Muenke syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the category of craniosynostosis. This condition is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance and stems from a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a craniosynostosis characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance, uni- or bicoronal synostosis, macrocephaly, midfacial hypoplasia, and developmental delay. This is due to a pro250 to agr (P250R) heterozygous mutation in the FGFR3 gene on chromosome 4p16.3. Moreover, Muenke syndrome is exactly synonymous with FGFR3-related craniosynostosis.

Lymphoproliferative syndrome is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease, which is characterized by immune dysregulation typically after viral infection, usually associated with Epstein-Barr viral infection. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: Combined immunodeficiency due to ITK deficiency.

X-linked lymphoproliferative syndrome 1 (XLP1) is a type of lymphoproliferative syndrome, which also falls under the category of an X-linked recessive disease. This condition is characterized by a type of inheritance that has a material basis in some X-linked recessive genes. It is defined as a lymphoproliferative syndrome that is marked by severe immune dysregulation following a viral infection. This dysregulation may manifest as severe or fatal mononucleosis, acquired hypogammaglobulinemia, hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis, and/or malignant lymphoma, all of which have a material basis in an X-linked mutation in the SH2D1A gene located on chromosome Xq25.

X-linked lymphoproliferative syndrome 2 is a type of lymphoproliferative syndrome, which falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. It is also a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. This syndrome is distinctly defined as a lymphoproliferative disorder characterized by its X-linked inheritance pattern and immune dysregulation following viral infection, which may manifest as lymphohistiocytosis, hypogammaglobulinemia, and/or splenomegaly. This condition is specifically linked to mutations in the XIAP gene located on chromosome Xq25. Furthermore, X-linked lymphoproliferative syndrome 2 is exactly synonymous with XIAP deficiency and XLP2.

Lymphoproliferative syndrome 1 (LPFS1) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of lymphoproliferative syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that originates from autosomal recessive inheritance and typically begins during childhood. The definition of lymphoproliferative syndrome 1 involves an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern and an early onset in childhood of Epstein-Barr virus-associated immune dysregulation. This can manifest as lymphoma, lymphomatoid granulomatosis, hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis, Hodgkin disease, and/or hypogammaglobulinemia, with the condition having a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the ITK gene on chromosome 5q32.

Lymphoproliferative syndrome 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of lymphoproliferative syndrome, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, persistent symptomatic Epstein-Barr virus-associated viremia, hypogammaglobulinemia, and impairment in specific antibody function and has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the CD27 gene on chromosome 12p13. Additionally, lymphoproliferative syndrome 2 is exactly synonymous with CD27 deficiency and LPFS2.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 2 (ARCI2), also known exactly as BROCQ congenital ichthyosiform erythroderma nonbullous form, NCIE1, and nonbullous congenital ichthyosiform erythroderma 1, is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis. This condition falls under the umbrella of diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. ARCI2 is specifically characterized by fine scales on the scalp, face, trunk, and limbs, marked palmoplantar hyperlinearity, hyperkeratosis, acanthosis, mild hypergranulosis, and a thickened stratum corneum. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ALOX12B gene on chromosome 17p13.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 3 (ARCI3), also known exactly as lamellar ichthyosis 5, is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis and falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. ARCI3 is defined as an autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis characterized by mild ichthyosis, fine scales on the scalp, face, trunk, and limbs, dark brown adherent scales on the neck, elbows, and knees, and hypohydrosis. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ALOXE3 gene located on chromosome 17p13.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 4a (ARCI4A), also known exactly as ICR2B and lamellar ichthyosis 2, is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis, which falls under the category of diseases with a basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is characterized by generalized ichthyosis and ectropion, having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ABCA12 gene on chromosome 2q35.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 4b (ARCI4B), also known with exact synonyms such as harlequin ichthyosis, harlequin type ichthyosis congenita, and harlequin type ichthyosis fetalis, is a specific type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis. It falls under the broader category of diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. This condition is characterized by severe neonatal ichthyosis accompanied by bilateral ectropion and eclabium, a flattened and rudimentary appearance of the nose and ears, constriction bands around the extremities, and frequently results in lethality during infancy. The material basis for ARCI4B is found in either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ABCA12 gene located on chromosome 2q35.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 5 is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis, which falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is specifically characterized by fine white or greyish-white scales, hyperkeratosis, moderate acanthosis, and moderate parakeratosis, and this condition has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CYP4F22 gene on chromosome 19p13. Additionally, autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 5 is exactly synonymous with ARCI5 and autosomal recessive congenital nonlamellar and nonerythrodermic ichthyosis.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 6 (ARCI6) is a specific type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis, which falls under the broader category of diseases that originate from some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as an autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis characterized by generalized ichthyosis, hyperkeratosis, parakeratosis, and moderate acanthosis. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NIPAL4 gene located on chromosome 5q33.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 7 (ARCI7) is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis, which falls under diseases with a basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as an autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis characterized by fine whitish scales, moderate to severe erythroderma, compact hyperkeratosis, hypergranulosis, acanthosis, and papillomatosis, with its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 12p11.2-q13.1.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 8 (ARCI8), also known exactly as lamellar ichthyosis 4 and late-onset lamellar ichthyosis, is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis. This condition is a type of something that at least has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. ARCI8 is characterized by diffuse lamellar ichthyosis, slight facial erythema, hyperkeratosis, orthokeratosis, hypergranulosis, and acanthosis. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the LIPN gene on chromosome 10q23.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 9 (ARCI9) is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis, which falls under the broader category of diseases that originate from some abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. It is specifically defined as an autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis characterized by various symptoms including fine erythrodermic scales, palmoplantar hyperlinearity, thick orthohyperkeratosis, hypergranulosis, moderate acanthosis, and mild alopecia. The condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the CERS3 gene on chromosome 15q26.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 10 (ARCI10) is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis, which is a category of diseases that have their basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is specifically characterized by generalized ichthyosis, moderade erythroderma, palmoplantar keratoderma, and hypergranulosis, with its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PNPLA1 gene on chromosome 6p21.

Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 11 is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis, which falls under the category of diseases with a basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is specifically characterized by ichthyosis, hypotrichosis, photophobia, corneal opacity, pingueculum, blepharitis, marked acanthosis, orthohyperkeratosis, and hyperkeratosis. This condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the ST14 gene on chromosome 11q24. It has several exact synonyms, including IFAH syndrome, IHS, autosomal recessive ichthyosis with hypotrichosis, hypotrichosis-congenital ichthyosis syndrome, ichthyosis and follicular atrophoderma with hypotrichosis and hypohidrosis, ichthyosis-follicular atrophoderma-hypotrichosis syndrome, ichthyosis-follicular atrophoderma-hypotrichosis-hypohidrosis syndrome, and ichthyosis-hypotrichosis syndrome.

NGLY1 deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease that also falls under the category of carbohydrate metabolic disorders. It is characterized by global developmental delay, hypotonia, abnormal involuntary movements, and alacrima or poor tear production. This condition is specifically caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the NGLY1 gene located on chromosome 1p24. Furthermore, NGLY1 deficiency is known by several exact synonyms, including NGLY1-CDDG, congenital disorder of deglycosylation, congenital disorder of glycosylation type Iv, and deficiency of N-glycanase 1.

Torsion dystonia 1 is categorized as a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of generalized dystonia that stems from autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a generalized dystonia characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of dystonia, which typically presents initially as focal, usually in the limbs, but often generalizes with age. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TOR1A gene on chromosome 9q34. Furthermore, torsion dystonia 1 is exactly synonymous with dystonia musculorum deformans.

Congenital Central Hypoventilation Syndrome (CCHS), also known as Ondine curse, Ondine syndrome, central congenital hypoventilation syndrome, and congenital central alveolar hypoventilation syndrome, is classified as an autonomic nervous system disease, a physical disorder, an autosomal dominant disease, and something that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance as well as a basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is characterized by a reduced responsiveness of the respiratory center to carbon dioxide, diminished pupillary light responses, and other symptoms related to defects in the autonomic nervous system. The material basis for most cases is commonly a heterozygous mutation in the PHOX2B gene on chromosome 4p13, and less frequently mutations in the RET, GDNF, EDN3, BDNF, or ASCL1 genes.

Chromosome 9p deletion syndrome, also precisely known as 9p syndrome, Alfi syndrome, or monosomy 9p syndrome, is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome.
