This syndrome is characterized by a distinctive set of features including trigonocephaly, a flattened occiput, midface hypoplasia, a long philtrum, a prominent forehead, a broad flat nasal bridge, anteverted nares, malformed external ears, hypertelorism, hypertonia, and delayed psychomotor development. The condition has its material basis in a contiguous gene deletion located on the short arm of chromosome 9.

Junctional epidermolysis bullosa with pyloric atresia is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it also falls under the category of junctional epidermolysis bullosa. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this type of junctional epidermolysis bullosa is defined as a junctional epidermolysis bullosa characterized by generalized blistering at birth with congenital atresia of the pylorus and, rarely, of other portions of the gastrointestinal tract, which has its material basis in mutations in the ITGB4 or ITGA6 genes. It is precisely known by several exact synonyms, including Carmi syndrome, JEB-PA, epidermolysis bullosa junctionalis with pyloric atresia, and junctional epidermolysis bullosa-pyloric atresia syndrome.

Epidermolysis bullosa simplex Dowling-Meara type is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of epidermolysis bullosa simplex. It is classified as a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. This type of epidermolysis bullosa simplex is characterized by generalized non-scarring skin blistering that often occurs in clusters, progressive hyperkeratosis of the palms and soles, and clumping of keratin filaments in basal epidermal cells. It is caused by a mutation in either the KRT5 or KRT14 genes, representing the most severe of the epidermolysis bullosa simplex types, which may lead to neonatal or infant lethality in some cases. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including EBS-gen sev, EBSDM, epidermolysis bullosa herpetiformis Dowling-Meara type, epidermolysis bullosa simplex, herpetiformis, and generalized severe epidermolysis bullosa simplex.

Epidermolysis bullosa simplex ogna type, also known precisely as EBS-O, EBS-Og, or EBSOG, is a specific form of autosomal dominant disease categorized under epidermolysis bullosa simplex. It is recognized by its unique characteristics, including skin blisters that originate in the deepest areas of the basal cell cytoplasm just above the hemidesmosomes, and skin bruising. This condition specifically arises from a heterozygous mutation in the PLEC1 gene located on chromosome 8q24. Additionally, it is described as a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Junctional epidermolysis bullosa Herlitz type is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is also a type of junctional epidermolysis bullosa. It is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a junctional epidermolysis bullosa characterized by the autosomal recessive inheritance of severe blisters and extensive erosions, localized to the skin and mucous membranes, resulting in a failure to thrive. This condition has its material basis in mutations in any one of the three genes encoding the subunits of laminin-5: LAMA3, LAMB3, and LAMC2. The Herlitz type is more severe than the related non-Herlitz type of junctional epidermolysis bullosa. It has several exact synonyms, including Herlitz type epidermolysis bullosa junctionalis, Herlitz-Pearson-type epidermolysis bullosa, JEB-H, JEB-Herlitz type, epidermolysis bullosa letalis, junctional epidermolysis bullosa generalisata gravis, and junctional epidermolysis bullosa, Herlitz-Pearson type.

Junctional epidermolysis bullosa non-Herlitz type is a form of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the broader category of junctional epidermolysis bullosa. It is characterized by skin and mucosal blistering, nail dystrophy or nail absence, and enamel hypoplasia. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in several genes, including COL17A1, ITGB4, and the three genes encoding the subunits of laminin-5: LAMA3, LAMB3, and LAMC2. Notably, the non-Herlitz type is less severe than the related Herlitz type of junctional epidermolysis bullosa. It is also known by several exact synonyms: GABEB, JEB-nH gen, JEN-nH, generalized atrophic benign epidermolysis bullosa, generalized junctional epidermolysis bullosa, non-Herlitz type, junctional epidermolysis bullosa generalisata mitis, and junctional epidermolysis bullosa, Disentis type.

Hand foot genital syndrome, also known by its exact synonyms HFGS and hand-foot-uterus syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome. It is characterized by a specific condition that stems from autosomal dominant inheritance and is situated at the intersection of the foot and hand. This syndrome is defined as a disorder marked by distal limb defects (including short thumbs and first toes, clinodactyly of the fifth fingers, delayed ossification of the wrist and ankle bones), urogenital defects, and originates from a heterozygous mutation in the HOXA13 gene on chromosome 7p15.

Methylmalonic aciduria due to methylmalonyl CoA mutase deficiency is a type of methylmalonic acidemia and falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is characterized by an accumulation of methylmalonic acid in the blood that is unresponsive to vitamin B12 therapy. This condition is caused by a mutation in the MUT gene located on chromosome 6p12.3. It is also known by its exact synonyms: methylmalonic acidemia due to methylmalonyl-CoA mutase deficiency, methylmalonic aciduria mut type, and vitamin B12-unresponsive methylmalonic aciduria.

Methylmalonic acidemia due to transcobalamin receptor defect is a specific type of methylmalonic acidemia and also falls into a broader category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is characterized by an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern involving low uptake of transcobalamin-bound cobalamin, yet normal conversion to adenosylcobalamin and methylcobalamin, a condition that arises due to a mutation in the CD320 gene. This condition is precisely referred to by two exact synonyms: methylmalonic acidemia, TCblR type, and methylmalonic aciduria due to transcobalamin receptor defect.

Methylmalonic acidemia cblA type is a form of methylmalonic acidemia which falls under diseases that have a basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a type of methylmalonic acidemia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, defects in the synthesis of AdoCbl, responsiveness to vitamin B12 therapy, and originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MMAA gene located on chromosome 4q31. This condition is also precisely referred to as methylmalonic aciduria cblA type and methylmalonic aciduria, vitamin B12-responsive due to a defect in synthesis of adenosylcobalamin cblA type.

Methylmalonic acidemia cblB type is classified as a form of methylmalonic acidemia and falls under the broader category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is specifically defined as a type of methylmalonic acidemia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance and defects in the synthesis of AdoCbl. This condition is responsive to vitamin B12 therapy and results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MMAB gene located on chromosome 12q24. Additionally, methylmalonic acidemia cblB type is precisely referred to as methylmalonic aciduria cblB type and also as methylmalonic aciduria, vitamin B12-responsive, due to defect in synthesis of adenosylcobalamin, cblB complementation type.

Pendred syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, specifically one that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by bilateral prelingual sensorineural hearing loss and euthyroid goiter, with its material basis being homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC26A4 gene on chromosome 7q. Pendred syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including TDH2B, congenital hypothyroidism due to dyshormonogenesis 2B, deafness with goiter, genetic defect in thyroid hormonogenesis 2B, goiter-deafness syndrome, and thyroid dyshormonogenesis 2B.

Doyne honeycomb retinal dystrophy (DHRD), also known as Doyne honeycomb degeneration of the retina, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and retinal drusen. It is characterized by a specific condition where there is at least a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of Doyne honeycomb retinal dystrophy describes it as a retinal drusen characterized by the accumulation of yellow-white deposits (drusen) beneath the retinal pigment epithelium in the posterior pole of the eye, forming a honeycomb pattern. This condition has its material basis in mutations in the EFEMP1 gene on chromosome 2p16.

Basal laminar drusen is a type of monogenic disease, retinal drusen, and something that at least has its basis in some gene. It is characterized by yellow-white deposits (drusen) that accumulate beneath the retinal pigment epithelium on Bruch membrane and has its material basis in mutations in the CFH gene on chromosome 1q31.3. Additionally, basal laminar drusen is also known by its exact synonyms: cuticular drusen, drusen of Bruch membrane, and early adult-onset grouped drusen.

Duane Radial Ray Syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases, indicating that it typically has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by upper limb anomalies, ocular anomalies, and in some cases, renal anomalies, stemming from a heterozygous mutation in the SALL4 gene on chromosome 20q13. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms: DR Syndrome, Duane Anomaly with Radial Ray Abnormalities and Deafness, Okihiro Syndrome, and Acrorenocular Syndrome.

Familial temporal lobe epilepsy 1 (FTLE1) is a specific type of temporal lobe epilepsy, and it is categorized as an autosomal dominant disease. This condition is defined by a form of temporal lobe epilepsy characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of partial seizures that originate from the temporal lobe. These seizures are often accompanied by auditory symptoms and are the result of heterozygous mutation in the LGI1 gene on chromosome 10q24. Additionally, FTLE1 is exactly synonymous with ETL1 and partial epilepsy with auditory features. It is also described as a type of condition that has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Familial Temporal Lobe Epilepsy 6 is a type of temporal lobe epilepsy and an autosomal dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a temporal lobe epilepsy that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 3q25-q26. Additionally, Familial Temporal Lobe Epilepsy 6 has the exact synonym ETL6.

Familial temporal lobe epilepsy 3 (FMTLE), also known as familial mesial temporal lobe epilepsy, is a specific type of temporal lobe epilepsy and autosomal dominant disease. It is defined as a temporal lobe epilepsy characterized by simple or complex partial seizures often accompanied by intense feelings of deja vu or altered awareness, with its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 4q13.2-q21.3. Additionally, it is a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Familial temporal lobe epilepsy 7 (ETL7) is a type of temporal lobe epilepsy and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a temporal lobe epilepsy that specifically involves autosomal dominant inheritance of focal seizures with prominent auditory symptoms, with its material basis being a heterozygous mutation in the RELN gene on chromosome 7q22. This condition falls under the category of diseases that, at a minimum, have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Familial temporal lobe epilepsy 5 (FTLE5), which is exactly synonymous with ETL5, is classified as a type of temporal lobe epilepsy. This condition is unique in that it is described both as an autosomal dominant and an autosomal recessive disease, indicating it has a material basis in genetic inheritance patterns that can be either autosomal dominant or autosomal recessive. Specifically, FTLE5 has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CPA6 gene located on chromosome 8q13, according to its definition.

Familial temporal lobe epilepsy 4 is a type of temporal lobe epilepsy and an autosomal dominant disease that notably has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is characterized as a temporal lobe epilepsy marked by autosomal dominant inheritance of occipitotemporal lobe epilepsy and migraine with visual aura, with this condition having a material basis in variation in the chromosome region 9q21-q22. Additionally, familial temporal lobe epilepsy 4 is precisely known by its exact synonyms: EPOLM, ETL4, and occipitotemporal lobe epilepsy and migraine with aura.

Familial temporal lobe epilepsy 8 (ETL8) is a type of temporal lobe epilepsy and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a temporal lobe epilepsy that involves autosomal dominant inheritance of complex partial seizures, which occasionally undergo secondary generalization. This condition specifically has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GAL gene located on chromosome 11q13. Additionally, familial temporal lobe epilepsy 8 is defined by its relation to autosomal dominant inheritance, indicating a genetic foundation in this mode of inheritance.

Familial Temporal Lobe Epilepsy 2 (ETL2) is a type of temporal lobe epilepsy, specifically an autosomal dominant disease that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a temporal lobe epilepsy characterized by the autosomal dominant inheritance of complex or partial seizures and childhood febrile seizures, with its material basis stemming from variation in the chromosome region 12q22-q23.3.

Sclerosteosis 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of sclerosteosis, which is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, Sclerosteosis 1 is defined as a sclerosteosis that arises from a homozygous mutation in the SOST gene located on chromosome 17q21. Additionally, Sclerosteosis 1 is exactly synonymous with SOST1.

Sclerosteosis 2 is a type of sclerosteosis and has an exact synonym, SOST2. It is characterized as both an autosomal dominant and an autosomal recessive disease, indicating that its material basis can be found in genetic inheritance patterns that are either autosomal dominant or autosomal recessive. Specifically, Sclerosteosis 2 is defined as a sclerosteosis that arises from either heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the LRP4 gene located on chromosome 11p11.

Immunodeficiency with hyper IgM type 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is also considered a type of Hyper IgM syndrome. It belongs to a category of diseases that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular syndrome is characterized by normal or elevated serum IgM levels with the absence of IgG, IgA, and IgE, leading to a profound susceptibility to bacterial infections. The condition results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the AICDA gene located on chromosome 12p13. 

It is known by several exact synonyms including AID deficiency, HIGM2, activation-induced cytidine deaminase deficiency, and hyper-IgM syndrome type 2. Furthermore, immunodeficiency with hyper IgM type 2 matches several external identifiers, such as ORDO:183666, GARD:10578, NCI:C129074, OMIM:605258, ORDO:101089, and UMLS_CUI:C1720956, indicating its recognition and categorization within various medical and genetic databases.

Immunodeficiency with hyper IgM type 5 is a subtype of autosomal recessive disease and hyper IgM syndrome, which falls into the category of conditions that at least have a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hyper IgM syndrome characterized by normal or increased serum IgM concentrations coupled with low or absent serum IgG, IgA, and IgE concentrations. This indicates a defect in the class-switch recombination (CSR) process due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the UNG gene on chromosome 12q23-q24.1. Immunodeficiency with hyper IgM type 5 is also known by its exact synonyms: HIGM5, hyper-IgM syndrome 5, hyper-IgM syndrome due to UNG deficiency, and hyper-IgM syndrome due to uracil N-glycosylase. It has been matched with broader and exact medical identifiers, including a broader match ORDO:183666 and exact matches to GARD:10581, OMIM:608106, ORDO:101092, and UMLS_CUI:C1720958.

Immunodeficiency with hyper IgM type 4 is a type of hyper IgM syndrome characterized by normal or increased serum IgM concentrations accompanied by low or absent serum IgG, IgA, and IgE concentrations. This indicates a defect in the class-switch recombination (CSR) process. It is also known by its exact synonyms HIGM4 and hyper-IgM syndrome type 4. This condition has a broader match with ORDO:183666 and exact matches with several identifiers, including GARD:10580, MESH:C564277, NCI:C564277, OMIM:608184, ORDO:101091, and UMLS_CUI:C1842413.

Familial chronic myelocytic leukemia like syndrome is a type of chronic myeloid leukemia that is characterized by the presence of chronic myelocytic leukemia in early infancy and the absence of the BCR/ABL fusion gene (Philadelphia chromosome). Additionally, familial chronic myelocytic leukemia like syndrome is exactly synonymous with familial CML-like syndrome.

    :has_definition "A skin disease characterized by thin, tightly adherent translucent skin with erosions at flexure sites, superficial vessels, typical facial dysmorphism, and generalized joint ankylosis. Prenatal signs may include intrauterine growth retardation, reduced fetal movements, polyhydramnios, and premature rupture of the membranes. Most infants die within the first week of life." ;
    :has_exact_match "GARD:1516",
        "MESH:C536920",
        "OMIM:PS275210",
        "ORDO:1662",
        "SNOMEDCT_US_2023_02_28:400128006",
        "UMLS_CUI:C0406585" ;
    :has_exact_synonym "Infantile restrictive dermopathy",
        "Lethal tight skin contracture syndrome",
        "hyperkeratosis-contracture syndrome"@en,
        "lethal restrictive dermopathy"@en,
        "tight skin contracture syndrome"@en .
text: Restrictive dermopathy is a type of skin disease defined by thin, tightly adherent translucent skin with erosions at flexure sites, superficial vessels, typical facial dysmorphism, and generalized joint ankylosis. It comes with prenatal signs that may include intrauterine growth retardation, reduced fetal movements, polyhydramnios, and premature rupture of the membranes, leading to most infants dying within the first week of life. The disease is also known exactly as Infantile restrictive dermopathy, Lethal tight skin contracture syndrome, hyperkeratosis-contracture syndrome, lethal restrictive dermopathy, and tight skin contracture syndrome. Moreover, restrictive dermopathy is precisely matched with several medical databases and classifications, including GARD:1516, MESH:C536920, OMIM:PS275210, ORDO:1662, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_02_28:400128006, and UMLS_CUI:C0406585.

X-linked juvenile retinoschisis 1 is a type of X-linked recessive disease, retinoschisis, and something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is also a type of something that at least has its existence starting during young adult onset. It is defined as a retinoschisis characterized by schisis (splitting) of the neural retina leading to reduced visual acuity in males due to having its material basis in the RS1 gene on chromosome Xp22. Furthermore, X-linked juvenile retinoschisis 1 has exact synonyms: X-linked juvenile retinoschisis, X-linked retinoschisis, and XLRS.

Autosomal recessive Robinow syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of Robinow syndrome, which is characterized by a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is a Robinow syndrome that manifests through autosomal recessive inheritance of severe skeletal dysplasia, characterized by distinct facial features such as frontal bossing, hypertelorism, and a broad nose, along with short-limbed dwarfism, vertebral segmentation, and genital hypoplasia. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ROR2 gene on chromosome 9q22. Additionally, autosomal recessive Robinow syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: COVESDEM syndrome, RRS, and costovertebral segmentation defect-mesomelia syndrome.

Autosomal dominant Robinow syndrome 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, Robinow syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of mesomelic limb shortening, genital hypoplasia, and distinctive facial features, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DVL1 gene on chromosome 1p36. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, DRS2.

Autosomal dominant Robinow syndrome 1 (ADRS1) is a type of Robinow syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and defined by a specific set of features: dysmorphic facial appearance resembling that of a fetus, mesomelic limb shortening, underdeveloped external genitalia in males, and abnormalities in the kidneys and vertebrae. These characteristics are the result of a heterozygous mutation in the WNT5A gene located on chromosome 3p. Additionally, Autosomal dominant Robinow syndrome 1 is exactly synonymous with DRS1.

Autosomal Dominant Robinow Syndrome 3 (ADRS3), also known as DRS3, is a type of Robinow syndrome, which falls under the broader category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is characterized by a specific set of features including mesomelia, genital hypoplasia, and distinctive facial features such as frontal bossing, prominent eyes, and a depressed nasal bridge. The basis for these characteristics is a heterozygous mutation in the DVL3 gene located on chromosome 3q27. This syndrome is a manifestation of autosomal dominant inheritance, highlighting its genetic foundation in autosomal dominant inheritance patterns.

Smith-Magenis Syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, which is precisely defined as a chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by a range of symptoms including mild-to-moderate infantile hypotonia, minor skeletal anomalies, prepubertal short stature, brachydactyly, ophthalmologic and otolaryngologic abnormalities, peripheral neuropathy, developmental delay, cognitive impairment, and behavioral abnormalities. The condition has its material basis in a 3.7-Mb interstitial deletion in chromosome 17p11.2 or, in some cases, by mutations in the RAI1 gene in the same region. Smith-Magenis Syndrome is also exactly synonymous with 17p11.2 microdeletion syndrome and chromosome 17p11.2 deletion syndrome.

T cell immunodeficiency congenital alopecia and nail dystrophy is a type of physical disorder, severe combined immunodeficiency, and autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by congenital alopecia, severe T-cell immunodeficiency, and ridging, pitting, or curving of all nails. This condition has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the FOXN1 gene on chromosome 17q11-q12, and it is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Furthermore, it is also known by exact synonyms such as alymphoid cystic thymic dysgenesis, severe T-cell immunodeficiency-congenital alopecia-nail dystrophy syndrome, and winged helix deficiency.

Dextro looped transposition of the great arteries is a type of congenital heart disease characterized by a complete inversion of the great vessels, where the aorta incorrectly arises from the right ventricle, and the pulmonary artery incorrectly arises from the left ventricle. It has several exact synonyms, including D-TGA, DTGA1, congenitally uncorrected transposition of the great arteries, congenitally uncorrected transposition of the great vessels, isolated ventriculoarterial discordance, and ventriculoarterial discordance with atrioventricular concordance.

Multiple types of congenital heart defects 6, also known as DTGA3 and dextro-looped transposition of the great arteries 3, is a type of congenital heart disease and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a congenital cardiac malformation that includes atrioventricular concordance and ventriculoarterial discordance. This disease has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GDF1 gene on chromosome 19p13 and is also considered to have a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Cleft lip palate ectodermal dysplasia syndrome is a type of syndrome that is also a type of autosomal recessive disease and is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by cleft lip, cleft palate, hypodontia, anodontia, microdontia, syndactyly, palmoplantar hyperkeratosis, onychodysplasia, and sparse hair, which has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the NECTIN1 gene on chromosome 11q23. It has exact synonyms: CLPED1, Margarita type of ectodermal dysplasia, Zlotogora-Zilberman-Tenenbaum syndrome, cleft lip/palate-syndactyly-pili torti syndrome, and syndactyly-ectodermal dysplasia-cleft/lip palate.

Congenital diarrhea is a type of physical disorder and a type of diarrhea, which is at least characterized by the symptom of some diarrhea and has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as diarrhea that is characterized by frequent loose or liquid bowel movements where the disease is present from birth.

Microvillus inclusion disease is a type of autosomal recessive disease, congenital diarrhea, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a congenital diarrhea characterized by the onset of intractable life-threatening watery diarrhea during infancy, lack of microvilli on the surface of enterocytes, and the occurrence of intracellular vacuolar structures containing microvilli. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MYO5B gene on chromosome 18q21. Furthermore, microvillus inclusion disease is exactly synonymous with Davidson disease, MVD, congenital familial protracted diarrhea with enterocyte brush-border abnormalities, congenital microvillus atrophy, diarrhea 2 with microvillus atrophy, and intractable diarrhea of infancy.

Congenital Diarrhea 5 with Tufting Enteropathy is a specific type of congenital diarrhea, which is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is also noted for having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is linked to abnormalities related to prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital diarrhea characterized by intractable diarrhea of infancy with villous atrophy, absence of inflammation, and intestinal epithelial cell dysplasia manifesting as focal epithelial tufts in the duodenum and jejunum. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EPCAM gene on chromosome 2p21. Additionally, Congenital Diarrhea 5 with Tufting Enteropathy is known by several exact synonyms, including DIAR5, Congenital Diarrhoea 5 with Tufting Enteropathy, Congenital Familial Intractable Diarrhea with Epithelial or Epithelium Abnormalities, Congenital Familial Intractable Diarrhoea with Epithelial or Epithelium Abnormalities, Congenital Tufting Enteropathy, and Tufting Enteropathy.

Congenital secretory sodium diarrhea 8, also known precisely as DIAR8, is classified as a type of secretory diarrhea, an autosomal recessive disease, and a physical disorder. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and symptoms that include diarrhea. Additionally, it is linked to abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. The disorder is specifically defined by a secretory diarrhea that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC9A3 gene located on chromosome 5p15.

Congenital diarrhea 7 with exudative enteropathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease and congenital diarrhea. It is characterized as having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and symptoms that include diarrhea. This condition also has its basis in some abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, congenital diarrhea 7 with exudative enteropathy is defined as a congenital diarrhea characterized by watery diarrhea, protein-losing enteropathy, patchy areas of dystrophic microvilli in the duodenum, and patchy areas of villous atrophy. This condition is caused by homozygous mutation in the DGAT1 gene on chromosome 8q24.3. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including congenital chronic diarrhea with exudative enteropathy, congenital chronic diarrhea with protein-losing enteropathy, congenital chronic diarrhoea with exudative enteropathy, congenital chronic diarrhoea with protein-losing enteropathy, and congenital diarrhoea 7 with exudative enteropathy.

Congenital Malabsorptive Diarrhea 4 is a type of congenital diarrhea, autosomal recessive disease, and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It also has symptoms that include diarrhea and its disease basis is rooted in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. This condition is defined as a congenital diarrhea that is characterized by chronic unremitting malabsorptive diarrhea and a profound dysgenesis of the enteroendocrine cells, which is caused by mutations in the gene encoding neurogenin-3 (NEUROG3) on chromosome 10q21.3. Additionally, Congenital Malabsorptive Diarrhea 4 is also known by its exact synonyms: congenital malabsorptive diarrhea due to paucity of enteroendocrine cells, congenital malabsorptive diarrhoea 4, congenital malabsorptive diarrhoea due to paucity of enteroendocrine cells, and enteric anendocrinosis.

Congenital diarrhea 6 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the broader category of congenital diarrhea. It is specifically characterized by a mild, early-onset chronic diarrhea. This condition is rooted in autosomal dominant inheritance and is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the GUCY2C gene on chromosome 12p12. Additionally, it is associated with symptoms of diarrhea and has its basis in some abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Congenital diarrhea 6 is also known by its exact synonyms: chronic diarrhea due to guanylate cyclase 2C overactivity, chronic diarrhoea due to guanylate cyclase 2C overactivity, and congenital diarrhoea 6.

Congenital secretory sodium diarrhea 3 is recognized as a type of secretory diarrhea, autosomal recessive disease, and physical disorder. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and exhibiting symptoms such as diarrhea. This condition also has its foundations in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, congenital secretory sodium diarrhea 3 is defined as a secretory diarrhea that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SPINT2 gene on chromosome 19q13.

Furthermore, congenital secretory sodium diarrhea 3 is also known by several exact synonyms, including congenital secretory sodium diarrhea 3 syndromic, congenital secretory sodium diarrhea 3 with or without other congenital anomalies, congenital secretory sodium diarrhoea 3, congenital secretory sodium diarrhoea 3 syndromic, and congenital secretory sodium diarrhoea 3 with or without other congenital anomalies.

EEC syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome, which is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by ectrodactyly, ectodermal dysplasia, and orofacial clefts (cleft lip-palate). EEC syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: Rudiger syndrome 1, Walker-Clodius syndrome, ectrodactyly, ectodermal dysplasia, and cleft lip-palate syndrome, and ectrodactyly-ectodermal dysplasia-clefting syndrome. Additionally, EEC syndrome has an exact match with the MESH identifier C536189.

Ectrodactyly ectodermal dysplasia and cleft lip palate syndrome 3 is a type of EEC syndrome and has the exact synonyms EEC syndrome 3 and EEC3. It is defined as an EEC syndrome characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of the absence of the central parts of the hands and feet, resulting in split-hand/foot malformation, ectodermal dysplasia, and cleft lip with or without cleft palate. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TP63 gene on chromosome 3q28.

Ectrodactyly ectodermal dysplasia and cleft lip palate syndrome 1 is a type of EEC syndrome, which is also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance that has a material basis in variation in the chromosome region 7q11.2-q21.3. Moreover, it has exact synonyms EEC syndrome 1 and EEC1.

Adult onset autosomal dominant demyelinating leukodystrophy (ADLD) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of leukodystrophy that begins in adulthood. It is characterized by a genetic basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and its existence typically starts during adult onset. Specifically, ADLD is defined as a leukodystrophy that manifests in the 4th or 5th decade of life with symptoms including autonomic abnormalities, pyramidal and cerebellar dysfunction, and symmetric demyelination of the central nervous system. This condition results from a heterozygous tandem genomic duplication that leads to an extra copy of the LMNB1 gene on chromosome 5q. ADLD is also known by several exact synonyms, including adult-onset autosomal dominant leukodystrophy and the autosomal-dominant or late-onset type Pelizaeus-Merzbacher disease.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy is a type of leukodystrophy and has the exact synonym HLD. It is defined as a leukodystrophy characterized by improper formation of the myelin sheath in the central nervous system, resulting in T2 hyperintensity and variable T1 signal on magnetic resonance imaging.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy, which fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of symptoms including nystagmus, impaired motor development, ataxia, choreoathetotic movements, dysarthria, and progressive spasticity, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GJC2 gene on chromosome 1q42. Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 2 is precisely synonymous with HLD2, PMLD1, Pelizaeus-Merzbacher-like disease 1, and Pelizaeus-Merzbacher-like disease due to GJC2 mutation.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 10 (HLD10) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy, which fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance that leads to progressive postnatal microcephaly, severely delayed psychomotor development, and hypomyelination due to a homozygous mutation in the PYCR2 gene on chromosome 1q42.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 4, also known precisely as HLD4, MitCHAP60 disease, Pelizaeus-Merzbacher-like disease due to HSPD1 mutation, and mitochondrial HSP60 chaperonopathy, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It falls under the broader category of hypomyelinating leukodystrophies and is specifically associated with conditions that fundamentally stem from autosomal recessive inheritance. Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 4 is characterized by a specific condition involving autosomal recessive inheritance of hypotonia, nystagmus, psychomotor developmental delay, and severe hypomyelinating leukoencephalopathy, which is due to a homozygous mutation in the HSPD1 gene located on chromosome 2q33.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 3 is a type of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy and an autosomal recessive disease, which is a category of diseases that at least have a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically characterized by an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern of early infantile onset of global developmental delay, lack of development, lack of speech acquisition, and peripheral spasticity. This condition is associated with decreased myelination in the central nervous system and is due to a homozygous mutation in the AIMP1 gene on chromosome 4q24. Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 3 is also known by its exact synonyms, HLD3 and Pelizaeus-Merzbacher-like disease due to AIMP1 mutation.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 9 (HLD9), also known exactly as RARS-related autosomal recessive hypomyelinating leukodystrophy, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy. It is specifically characterized by a condition that, at its core, involves autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of HLD9 includes it being a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy identified by delayed psychomotor development, spasticity, and nystagmus beginning in the first year of life, with this condition having its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the RARS gene located on chromosome 5q34.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 11 (HLD11) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a kind of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, marked by delayed psychomotor development, and other neurologic features associated with hypomyelination. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the POLR1C gene located on chromosome 6p21.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 5 (HLD5), also known precisely as hypomyelination-congenital cataract syndrome, is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of hypomyelinating leukodystrophies. It is specifically defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance involving congenital cataract, progressive neurologic impairment, and diffuse myelin deficiency with the condition having its material basis in homozygous mutation in the FAM126A gene located on chromosome 7p15. This condition is also a type of disorder that essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Hypomyelinating Leukodystrophy 7 (HLD7) is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of hypomyelinating leukodystrophies. It is characterized by an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the POLR3A gene located on chromosome 10q22. This disease manifests in childhood with a progressive motor decline indicated by symptoms such as spasticity, ataxia, tremor, and cerebellar signs, alongside mild cognitive regression. HLD7 is known by several exact synonyms, including TACH syndrome, Ataxia-Delayed Dentition-Hypomyelination syndrome, also referred to as Odontoleukodystrophy, Dentoleukoencephalopathy, Hypomyelination-Cerebellar Atrophy-Hypoplasia of the Corpus Callosum syndrome, Leukodystrophy with Oligodontia, Leukoencephalopathy-Ataxia-Hypodontia-Hypomyelination syndrome, and Tremor-Ataxia-Central Hypomyelination syndrome.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 13 (HLD13) is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also categorized under hypomyelinating leukodystrophies. It is defined as a condition that arises due to an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern linked specifically to a homozygous mutation in the C11ORF73 gene located on chromosome 11q14. This condition is characterized by an infantile onset of delayed psychomotor development, axial hypotonia, and spasticity, which are associated with delayed myelination and periventricular white matter abnormalities. Moreover, HLD13 is known by the exact synonym "HLD13."

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 12 (HLD12) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a category of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, HLD12 is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy distinguished by autosomal recessive inheritance, which involves severely delayed or even a lack of psychomotor development noticeable in the first months of life, acquired microcephaly, and delayed myelination. This condition is due to a homozygous mutation in the VPS11 gene located on chromosome 11q23.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 8 (HLD8) is a type of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy and an autosomal recessive disease. It is recognized as a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, HLD8 is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, with an early childhood onset of cerebellar ataxia and mild intellectual disabilities. These symptoms are associated with diffuse hypomyelination and the variable development of oligodontia and/or hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, caused by compound heterozygous mutation in the POLR3B gene on chromosome 12q23.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 6 (HLD6), also known exactly as H-ABC, HABC, or hypomyelination with atrophy of basal ganglia and cerebellum, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It falls under the category of hypomyelinating leukodystrophies and is specifically a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. HLD6 is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by the onset in infancy or early childhood of delayed motor development and gait instability. This progresses to extrapyramidal movement disorders, progressive spastic tetraplegia, ataxia, and hypomyelination, alongside cerebellar atrophy and atrophy or disappearance of the putamen. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the TUBB4A gene located on chromosome 19p13.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Lubs type is classified as a form of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, as well as a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome. It represents an intersection of conditions that have a material basis in some chromosome and duplication. This specific disability is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by a spectrum of symptoms including moderate to profound intellectual disability, infantile hypotonia, mild dysmorphic features, poor speech development, autistic features, seizures, progressive spasticity, and recurrent infections in males. The underlying cause is identified as the duplication or triplication of the MECP2 gene on chromosome Xq28. Furthermore, it is recognized by various exact synonyms: Lubs X-linked mental retardation syndrome, MECP2 duplication syndrome, MRXSL, X-linked intellectual disability-hypotonia-recurrent Infections syndrome, mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic, Lubs type, and mental retardation, X-linked, with recurrent respiratory infections.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 5 is a specific type within the broader categories of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and X-linked recessive diseases. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that features a range of variable characteristics including choreoathetosis, hydrocephalus, Dandy-Walker malformation, seizures, and deposits of iron or calcium in the brain, all of which are rooted in a mutation in the AP1S2 gene located on chromosome Xp22. Moreover, this condition is known by several exact synonyms, including Fried syndrome, MRX59, MRXS21, Mental Retardation, X-linked syndromic 5, Pettigrew syndrome, X-linked intellectual disability-Dandy-Walker malformation-basal ganglia disease-seizures syndrome, X-linked mental retardation 59, X-linked mental retardation with Dandy-Walker malformation, basal ganglia disease, and seizures, syndromic X-linked mental retardation 21, and syndromic X-linked mental retardation Fried type.

Mehmo syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is also a form of X-linked recessive disease. This condition is characterized by a severe intellectual deficit, epilepsy, microcephaly, hypogenitalism, and obesity, with the occurrence of growth delay and diabetes varying among individuals. The syndrome has its material basis in a variation in the chromosome region Xp22.13-p21.1, which falls under the category of X-linked recessive inheritance. Mehmo syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including MRXS20, MRXS25, X-linked intellectual disability-epileptic seizures-hypogenitalism-microcephaly-obesity syndrome, mental retardation, epileptic seizures, hypogonadism and hypogenitalism, microcephaly, and obesity, along with syndromic X-linked mental retardation 20 and syndromic X-linked mental retardation 25.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Snyder type is a form of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that also qualifies as an X-linked recessive disease. This condition is rooted in X-linked recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a range of symptoms including mild to profound intellectual disability, facial asymmetry, marfanoid and asthenic habitus, unsteady gait, a thickened lower lip, nasal dysarthic speech, a narrow or cleft palate, osteoporosis, kyphoscoliosis, long great toes, short stature, pectus carinatum, and myopia. These manifestations are due to mutations in the SMS gene located on chromosome Xp22. The disorder is alternatively known by several exact synonyms: SRS, Snyder-Robinson mental retardation syndrome, Snyder-Robinson syndrome, mental retardation, X-linked, Snyder-Robinson type, and spermine synthase deficiency.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 17 is a type of both syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and X-linked recessive disease, and it also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by global developmental delay, delayed motor development, lack of speech development, intellectual disability, alacrima (lack of tear production), and in some patients, achalasia (a disorder affecting the ability to swallow) and/or anisocoria (unequal pupil sizes). This condition has its material basis in variations in the chromosome region Xp21.1-p11.23. Furthermore, Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 17 is also known by its exact synonyms: X-linked mental retardation with alacrima and achalasia, intellectual disability-alacrima-achalasia syndrome, and mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 17.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 12 is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by a severe intellectual deficit, mutism, epilepsy, growth retardation or failure, and recurrent infections, which has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region Xp11. It also has exact synonyms, including X-linked intellectual disability, Wilson type, and mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 12.

Prieto syndrome, also known exactly as Prieto-Badia-Mulas syndrome and X-linked intellectual disability-dysmorphism-cerebral atrophy syndrome, is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by intellectual disability, facial dysmorphism, patella luxation, clinodactyly, subcortical cerebral atrophy, and abnormal growth of the teeth, with its material basis in variation in the chromosome region Xp11-q21. This condition is something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Hedera type is a specific form of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is characterized by mild to moderate mental retardation and epilepsy, with the condition stemming from a mutation in the ATP6AP2 gene located on chromosome Xp11. This type of disability is also precisely known by several synonyms, including MRXE, MRXSH, X-linked mental retardation with epilepsy, and mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic, Hedera type.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Najm type is a specific form of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by severe intellectual disability, microcephaly with pontine and cerebellar hypoplasia, resulting from a heterozygous mutation or deletion in the CASK gene on chromosome Xp11. This condition is precisely referred to by several exact synonyms, including MICPCH, X-linked intellectual disability-microcephaly-pontocerebellar hypoplasia syndrome, and mental retardation and microcephaly with pontine and cerebellar hypoplasia.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 7 is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by an intellectual deficit, obesity, hypogonadism, and tapering fingers, which has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region Xp11.3-q22. It has exact synonyms: MRXS7, X-linked intellectual disability, Ahmad type, and mental retardation, X-linked syndromic 7.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Claes Jensen type is a form of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and is classified as a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by a severe intellectual deficit along with variable clinical manifestations that include spasticity, cryptorchidism, maxillary hypoplasia, alopecia areata, epilepsy, short stature, impaired speech, and behavioral problems. These characteristics are due to a mutation in the KDM5C gene on chromosome Xp11, indicating that it has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. Furthermore, this condition is known by several exact synonyms, including MRXSCJ, MRXSJ, mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic, Claes-Jensen type, syndromic X-linked intellectual disability due to JARID1C mutation, and syndromic X-linked mental retardation JARID1C-related.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability type 10 is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is characterized by a mild intellectual deficit associated with choreoathetosis and abnormal behavior, with its material basis in a mutation in the HSD17B10 gene on chromosome Xp11.22. This condition is also precisely known by several exact synonyms, including HSD10 deficiency, atypical type; HSD10 disease, atypical type; MRXS10; X-linked intellectual disability-choreoathetosis-abnormal behavior syndrome; and mental retardation, X-linked syndromic 10.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Turner type is a specific form of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is characterized by a moderate to severe intellectual deficit in boys and a moderate intellectual deficit in girls, alongside features such as macrocephaly, and in some cases, holoprosencephaly. The condition is caused by mutations in the HUWE1 gene located on chromosome Xp11.22. This disorder is also known by several exact synonyms, including Brooks-Wisniewski-Brown syndrome, MRXST, X-linked intellectual disability, Brooks type, mental retardation and macrocephaly syndrome, and mental retardation, X-linked syndromic, Turner type.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Siderius type is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, X-linked recessive disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by mild to moderate intellectual disability, a long face, and a broad nasal tip with, in some cases, cleft lip/palate, preaxial polydactyly, and cryptorchidism, and has its material basis in mutation in the PHF8 gene on chromosome Xp11.22. The syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Siderius type has exact synonyms including MRXSSD, Siderius X-linked mental retardation syndrome, Siderius-Hamel syndrome, and mental retardation syndrome, X-linked, Siderius type.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Shrimpton type is a specific form of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by severe mental retardation, microcephaly, speech delay, and variable short stature, which arises from variation in the chromosomal region Xq12-q21.31. Furthermore, this condition is precisely synonymous with MRXS9 and mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 9.

Wilson Turner Syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is also recognized as a type of X-linked recessive disease. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, Wilson Turner Syndrome is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that features intellectual disability, truncal obesity, gynecomastia, hypogonadism, dysmorphic facial features, and short stature. This condition arises from hemizygous mutation in the LAS1L gene on chromosome Xq12. Furthermore, Wilson Turner Syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including MRXS6, WTS, X-linked intellectual disability-gynecomastia-obesity syndrome, mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 6, and mental retardation, X-linked, with gynecomastia and obesity.

Miles Carpenter syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by severe intellectual deficit, microcephaly, exotropia, distal muscle wasting, and low digital arches. This condition has its material basis in variation in the chromosomal region Xq13-q22. It is also precisely referred to as MCS, MRXS4, X-linked intellectual disability, Miles-Carpenter type, mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 4, and mental retardation, X-linked, with congenital contractures and low fingertip arches.

Corpus Callosum Agenesis Intellectual Disability Coloboma Micrognathia Syndrome is categorized as a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. This condition is defined by a collection of characteristics, including agenesis of the corpus callosum, intellectual disability, ocular coloboma, micrognathia, sensorineural hearing loss, skeletal anomalies, and short stature. These symptoms are due to a mutation in the IGBP1 gene located on chromosome Xq13.1. Furthermore, this syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including Graham-Cox Syndrome, MRXS28, Corpus Callosum, Agenesis of, with Mental Retardation, Ocular Coloboma and Micrognathia, and Mental Retardation, X-linked, Syndromic 28.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 34 is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by delayed psychomotor development, intellectual disability, impaired speech, dysmorphic facial features, and mild structural brain abnormalities, including thickening of the corpus callosum. This condition is caused by a mutation in the NONO gene on chromosome Xq13. It is also known by several exact synonyms: MRXS34, MRXSML, macrocephaly-intellectual disability-left ventricular non-compaction syndrome, mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 34, and syndromic X-linked mental retardation Mircsof-Langouet type.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Abidi type is a form of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by various symptoms including intellectual disability, potential short stature, small head circumference, sloping forehead, hearing loss, abnormally shaped ears, and small testes. This condition arises from a variation in the chromosomal region Xq13.2. It is also known precisely by the synonyms MRXSAB, mental retardation, X-linked syndromic, Abidi type, and syndromic X-linked mental retardation Abidi type.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, Chudley-Schwartz type, is a specific form of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is characterized by moderate intellectual disability, seizures, dysmorphic facial features, and in some older patients, a slowly progressive unsteady gait and progressive weakness. The condition is defined by a variation in the chromosomal region Xq21.33-q23 and is known to at least manifest the symptom of progressive weakness. It has several exact synonyms, including MRXSCS, X-linked mental retardation with seizures, hypogammaglobinemia, and gait disturbance, as well as mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic, Chudley-Schwartz type.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, Nascimento type, is a specific category within syndromic X-linked intellectual disabilities. It is defined as a condition characterized by intellectual disability accompanied by distinctive dysmorphic features. These features include a large head, synophrys (joined eyebrows), prominent supraorbital ridges, almond-shaped and deep-set eyes, large ears, a wide mouth, a myxedematous appearance, hirsutism (excessive hair growth), abnormal hair whorls, micropenis, and onychodystrophy (nail disorder). The material basis for this condition is a mutation in the UBE2A gene located on chromosome Xq24. Additionally, this condition is precisely referred to by the synonyms "X-linked intellectual disability-nail dystrophy-seizures syndrome" and "mental retardation, X-linked syndromic, Nascimento-type."

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 14 is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and has an exact synonym: mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 14. It is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by a range from mild to severe intellectual disability, autistic features, a slender build, poor musculature, a long, thin face, a high-arched palate, a high nasal bridge, and pectus deformities. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the UPF3B gene on chromosome Xq24.

    :has_definition "A syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by intellectual deficit, muscle wasting, short stature, hypogonadism, and abnormal gait, with variable occurrence of prominent lower lip, kyphosis, joint hyperextensibility, tremor, decreased fine motor coordination and impaired speech that has_material_basis_in mutation in the CUL4B gene on chromosome Xq23." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "Cabezas syndrome; syndromic X-linked mental retardation 15"@en,
        "MRSS"@en,
        "MRXS15"@en,
        "MRXSC"@en,
        "X-linked mental retardation with short stature"@en,
        "X-linked mental retardation with short stature, hypogonadism, and abnormal gait"@en,
        "mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 15"@en,
        "mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 15 (Cabezas type)"@en .
text: Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Cabezas type is a specific category of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by an intellectual deficit, muscle wasting, short stature, hypogonadism, and abnormal gait. It also variably features a prominent lower lip, kyphosis, joint hyperextensibility, tremor, decreased fine motor coordination, and impaired speech. The condition is caused by a mutation in the CUL4B gene located on chromosome Xq23. It is also known by several exact synonyms including Cabezas syndrome, syndromic X-linked mental retardation 15, MRSS, MRXS15, MRXSC, X-linked mental retardation with short stature, X-linked mental retardation with short stature, hypogonadism, and abnormal gait, mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 15, and mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 15 (Cabezas type).

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 94 is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is characterized by moderate intellectual disability with variable occurrence of asthenic body habitus, dysmorphic features, autistic features, macrocephaly, seizures, myoclonic jerks, and hyporeflexia. This condition has its material basis in mutation in the GRIA3 gene on chromosome Xq25. It is exactly synonymous with MRX94, MRXS29, mental retardation, X-linked 94, syndromic X-linked intellectual disability due to GRIA3 anomalies, syndromic X-linked mental retardation 29, and syndromic X-linked mental retardation Wu type.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Raymond type is a specific kind of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. This condition is defined by intellectual disability and marfanoid habitus, stemming from a mutation in the ZDHHC9 gene located on chromosome Xq26.1. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including MRXSR, X-linked syndromic intellectual developmental disorder Raymond type, and mental retardation, X-linked syndromic, Raymond type.

Christianson syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and is also classified as a type of X-linked dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. Specifically, Christianson syndrome is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by severe developmental delay, intellectual disability, microcephaly, impaired speech, ataxia, hypotonia, and early-onset seizures, which has its material basis in mutation in the SLC9A6 gene on chromosome Xq26. It is known by several exact synonyms, including MRXSCH, X-linked Angelman-like syndrome, X-linked intellectual disability, South African type, X-linked intellectual disability-craniofacial dysmorphism-epilepsy-ophthalmoplegia-cerebellar atrophy syndrome, mental retardation, X-linked syndromic, Christianson type, and mental retardation, microcephaly, epilepsy, and ataxia syndrome. Additionally, Christianson syndrome has a broader match with MESH:C567484 and an exact match with MESH:C537450.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability Shashi type is a form of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by a moderate intellectual deficit, obesity, macroorchidism, and a characteristic facies. This condition has a material basis in a mutation in the RBMX gene located on chromosome Xq26. This condition is also exactly synonymous with several terms including MRXS11, SMRXS, Shashi X-linked mental retardation syndrome, X-linked mental retardation Shashi type, mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 11, Shashi type, and syndromic X-linked intellectual disability type 11.

X-linked intellectual disability psychosis macroorchidism syndrome is a specific type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by a moderate intellectual deficit, manic-depressive psychosis, pyramidal signs, and macroorchidism, which is caused by a mutation in the MECP2 gene on chromosome Xq28. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including Lindsay-Burn syndrome, MRXS13, PPM-X, X-linked mental retardation 79, X-linked mental retardation with spasticity, mental retardation with psychosis, pyramidal signs, and macroorchidism, and mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 13.

X-linked intellectual disability cardiomegaly congestive heart failure syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that also qualifies as a condition with at least some heart failure symptoms. This syndrome is characterized by intellectual disability, delayed psychomotor development, seizures, large joint contractures, cardiac abnormalities, and abnormal positioning of the thumbs, which is due to a mutation in the CLIC2 gene on chromosome Xq28. It is precisely known by its exact synonyms MRXS32 and mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic 32.

Deafness intellectual disability Martin-Probst type syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by severe bilateral deafness, intellectual disability, umbilical hernia, and abnormal dermatoglyphics. This condition occurs due to a variation on the X chromosome. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with both Martin-Probst syndrome and mental retardation, X-linked, syndromic, Martin-Probst type.

Griscelli syndrome is a type of disease that is autosomal recessive, falls under the category of integumentary system diseases, and is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a silvery gray sheen of the hair and hypopigmentation of the skin. Moreover, Griscelli syndrome is also known by exact synonyms such as Chediak-Higashi-like syndrome, Griscelli-Prunieras syndrome, and partial albinism-immunodeficiency syndrome.

Griscelli syndrome type 1 is a specific type of Griscelli syndrome characterized by a silvery gray sheen of the hair, hypopigmentation of the skin, and neurological impairment without immunodeficiency. This condition is caused by mutations in the MYO5A gene located on chromosome 15q21.2. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including GS1, Griscelli syndrome with neurological impairment, Griscelli syndrome, cutaneous and neurological type, Griscelli-Prunieras syndrome type 1, and hypopigmentation-neurologic impairment syndrome.

Griscelli syndrome type 2 is a specific type of Griscelli syndrome, characterized by a silvery gray sheen of the hair, hypopigmentation of the skin, and immunodeficiency, which may or may not be accompanied by neurologic impairment. This condition is caused by a mutation in the RAB27A gene located on chromosome 15q21.3. It is also known by several exact synonyms including GS2, Griscelli syndrome with hemophagocytic syndrome, Griscelli-Prunieras syndrome type 2, PAID syndrome, hypopigmentation-immunodeficiency with or without neurologic impairment syndrome, and partial albinism and immunodeficiency syndrome.

Griscelli syndrome type 3, which is a type of Griscelli syndrome, is characterized by an isolated silvery gray sheen of the hair and hypopigmentation of the skin. This condition arises due to mutations in the MLPH or MYO5A genes. It is also precisely referred to as GS3 and Griscelli-Prunieras syndrome type 3.

Isolated microphthalmia 6 (IM6) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific manifestation of isolated microphthalmia. It is characterized by a condition that inherently involves a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. IM6 is defined as an isolated microphthalmia characterized by its autosomal recessive inheritance pattern, a reduction in eye size particularly limited to the posterior segment of the eye, extreme hyperopia, and a short axial length. This condition is the result of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PRSS56 gene located on chromosome 2q37. Furthermore, isolated microphthalmia 6 is also known by its exact synonyms, MCOP6 and posterior nonsyndromic microphthalmia.

Isolated microphthalmia 4 is a type of monogenic disease, isolated microphthalmia, and something that at least has its basis in some gene. It is defined as an isolated microphthalmia that has a material basis in mutation in the GDF6 gene on chromosome 8q22. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym MCOP4.

Isolated microphthalmia 5, also precisely known as MCOP5, microphthalmia-retinitis pigmentosa-foveoschisis-optic disc drusen syndrome, and posterior microphthalmia with retinitis pigmentosa, foveoschisis, and optic disc drusen, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, as well as a form of isolated microphthalmia. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of posterior microphthalmia, hypermetropia, night blindness, decreased visual acuity, reduced macular reflex, scleral thickening, impaired rod and cone responses on ERG, foveoschisis, and in some patients, retinal pigment epithelium atrophy, arteriolar attenuation, angle-closure glaucoma, and optic disc drusen. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MFRP gene on chromosome 11q23 and is a manifestation of something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Isolated microphthalmia 7 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of isolated microphthalmia. It is defined as an isolated microphthalmia characterized by unilateral microphthalmia that has its material basis caused by a mutation in the GDF3 gene on chromosome 12p13. This condition is also precisely known as MCOP7. Additionally, it is categorized as something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Isolated Microphthalmia 2 (MCOP2) is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, as well as a specific form of isolated microphthalmia. It is defined as an isolated microphthalmia characterized by the autosomal recessive inheritance of bilateral profound microphthalmia without associated anomalies and with normal intelligence, which has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CHX10 gene on chromosome 14q24. This condition is also indicative of diseases that have at least a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Isolated microphthalmia 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of isolated microphthalmia, which is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an isolated microphthalmia that has its material basis in variation in the chromosomal region 14q32. Additionally, isolated microphthalmia 1 is exactly synonymous with MCOP1.

Isolated microphthalmia 8 (IM8) is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of isolated microphthalmia. Furthermore, it is specified as a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Its definition describes IM8 as an isolated microphthalmia characterized by bilateral severe microphthalmia, where the autosomal recessive inheritance results from a homozygous mutation in the ALDH1A3 gene located on chromosome 15q26. Additionally, IM8 is precisely synonymous with MCOP8.

Isolated microphthalmia 3 (MCOP3) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of isolated microphthalmia. It is defined as an isolated microphthalmia characterized by clinical anophthalmia and/or microphthalmia, which has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the RAX gene on chromosome 18q21. Additionally, it falls under the category of conditions that at least have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Hereditary neuropathy with liability to pressure palsies (HNPP) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of neuropathy that essentially has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by symptoms including muscle weakness. Specifically, HNPP is a neuropathy defined by autosomal dominant inheritance featuring peroneal muscle weakness, peripheral neuropathy, hyporeflexia, tomacula, segmental demyelination/remyelination, and decreased motor nerve conduction, which is attributed to the deletion or point mutation of the PMP22 gene on chromosome 17p12. Furthermore, hereditary neuropathy with liability to pressure palsies is also known by several exact synonyms: HNPP, current pressure-sensitive neuropathy, familial recurrent polyneuropathy, heterozygous microdeletion 17p11.2p12, potato-grubbing palsy, tomaculous neuropathy, and tulip-bulb digger's palsy.

Norrie disease is a type of syndrome that is also a specific form of X-linked recessive disease, characterized by having at least a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by degenerative and proliferative changes of the neuroretina, resulting in congenital blindness. Additionally, about 50% of patients experience progressive mental disorders, and approximately 33% of patients suffer from sensorineural deafness. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the NDP gene located on chromosome Xp11. Norrie disease is also known by several exact synonyms including Episkopi blindness, Norrie-Warburg disease, and atrophia bulborum hereditaria.

Leri Weill Dyschondrosteosis is a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by abnormal shortening of the forearms and lower legs, abnormal misalignment of the wrist (Madelung deformity of the wrist), and associated short stature. It has a material basis in heterozygous defects in the pseudoautosomal genes SHOX or SHOXY, or by deletion of the SHOX downstream regulatory domain.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 9 (DEE9) is a type of X-linked dominant disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by an entity that inherently has a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. DEE9 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by the onset of seizures in infancy and varying degrees of intellectual impairment in females, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding protocadherin-19 (PCDH19) located on chromosome Xq22. Additionally, DEE9 is known by several exact synonyms, including EFMR (Epilepsy Female with Mental Retardation), EIEE9 (Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 9), Juberg Hellman syndrome, Early Infantile Female-Limited Epileptic Encephalopathy, and Female Restricted Epilepsy with Mental Retardation, emphasizing its various aspects and the specific population it affects.

Osteoporosis pseudoglioma syndrome, also precisely known as OPPG and the ocular form of osteogenesis imperfecta, is classified as a syndrome and a specific type of autosomal recessive disease, which essentially has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by congenital or infancy-onset blindness, very low bone mass, decreased trabecular bone volume, severe juvenile-onset osteoporosis and spontaneous fractures, pseudoglioma, and microphthalmia. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LRP5 gene located on chromosome 11q13.

Annular pancreas is a type of pancreas disease characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance. It involves the head of the pancreas forming a ring around the second portion of the duodenum, often leading to duodenal stenosis.

Pemphigus vulgaris is a type of pemphigus characterized by autosomal dominant blisters and erosions on the skin and mucous membranes, caused by autoantibodies to intercellular cement substance. It also has the exact synonym familial pemphigus vulgaris.

Pierson syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by nephrotic syndrome with diffuse mesangial sclerosis, proteinuria, microcoria, absence of the pupillary dilator muscle in the iris, ciliary muscle atrophy, and abnormal eye development including lens-shape, retinal, and corneal anomalies. This condition arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LAMB2 gene on chromosome 3p21. Moreover, Pierson syndrome is exactly synonymous with microcoria-congenital nephrosis syndrome.

Potocki-Lupski syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome defined by a chromosomal duplication syndrome characterized by hypotonia, failure to thrive, mental retardation, pervasive developmental disorders, and congenital anomalies. This condition has its material basis in the duplication of a region of chromosome 17p11.2. It is also precisely known as 17p11.2 microduplication syndrome, chromosome 17p11.2 duplication syndrome, and trisomy 17p11.2.

Autosomal recessive pseudohypoaldosteronism type 1 (PHA1B, also known as autosomal recessive PHA 1) is a specific type of disease that falls under both the broader categories of autosomal recessive diseases and pseudohypoaldosteronism. It is characterized by a condition that inherently involves autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular form of pseudohypoaldosteronism is defined by renal salt wasting and elevated levels of sodium in sweat, stool, and saliva, which arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in one of three genes (SCNN1A, SCNN1B, or SCNN1G) that encode subunits of the epithelial sodium channel (ENaC).

Autosomal dominant pseudohypoaldosteronism type 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, pseudohypoaldosteronism, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a pseudohypoaldosteronism characterized by salt wasting resulting from renal unresponsiveness to mineralocorticoids, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NR3C2 gene on chromosome 4q31. Moreover, autosomal dominant pseudohypoaldosteronism type 1 has the exact synonyms PHA1A and autosomal dominant PHA 1.

Right atrial isomerism is a type of visceral heterotaxy, autosomal recessive disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a visceral heterotaxy characterized by a complete atrioventricular septal defect with a common atrium and univentricular AV connection, total anomalous pulmonary drainage, and transposition or malposition of the great arteries, which has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the GDF1 gene on chromosome 19p12. Furthermore, right atrial isomerism is exactly synonymous with Ivemark syndrome and asplenia with cardiovascular anomalies.

Septooptic dysplasia is a type of autosomal genetic disease and syndrome that at least has a material basis in some autosomal inheritance. It is characterized by the classical triad of optic nerve hypoplasia, pituitary gland hypoplasia, and midline brain defects, which have a material basis in mutation in the HESX1 gene on chromosome 3p14. This condition is also precisely known as De Morsier syndrome, SOD, and septo-optic dysplasia.
